1
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:11,840
Hello, everyone, and welcome
to lecture 9 of CME 295.

2
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:15,560
So as today is a
kind of a special day

3
00:00:15,560 --> 00:00:20,680
because we're having the last
lecture of the entire course.

4
00:00:20,680 --> 00:00:24,120
So the menu for today
will be a little different

5
00:00:24,120 --> 00:00:26,520
compared to usual.

6
00:00:26,520 --> 00:00:31,120
We're going to try to divide
the lecture in three parts.

7
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:33,000
So in the first
part, we're going

8
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:38,760
to recap actually what we
did in the entire class

9
00:00:38,760 --> 00:00:44,000
just to see how different
pieces kind of fit together.

10
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:46,960
In the second part,
we'll look at some topics

11
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:50,600
that are particularly
trending in 2025

12
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:54,640
and what we think are going to
be trending in the near future.

13
00:00:54,640 --> 00:01:00,680
And then the third part will be
more way for us to just conclude

14
00:01:00,680 --> 00:01:05,200
and next steps for all of you.

15
00:01:05,200 --> 00:01:07,520
Does that sound good?

16
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:08,900
Cool.

17
00:01:08,900 --> 00:01:13,440
So with that, we're going to
start with the first part, which

18
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:16,000
what I mentioned is
about recapping what

19
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,560
we did this entire quarter.

20
00:01:19,560 --> 00:01:22,040
So nothing new here
is just a way for us

21
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:24,680
to piece everything together.

22
00:01:24,680 --> 00:01:27,820
So if you remember
a lot of weeks ago,

23
00:01:27,820 --> 00:01:30,520
I believe it's like
maybe 10 weeks ago,

24
00:01:30,520 --> 00:01:35,520
we had lecture 1, which was
focused on understanding

25
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:38,000
what transformers were.

26
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:40,640
So at the very
beginning of the class,

27
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:44,560
we didn't even how we
could process text.

28
00:01:44,560 --> 00:01:46,160
So I guess the
first step that we

29
00:01:46,160 --> 00:01:52,040
saw was this tokenization step,
which consists of dividing

30
00:01:52,040 --> 00:01:55,360
the input into atomic units.

31
00:01:55,360 --> 00:01:59,730
And so here, the way
we divide the text

32
00:01:59,730 --> 00:02:03,330
is something that is
arbitrary in some sense.

33
00:02:03,330 --> 00:02:08,009
So we have different algorithms
that allow us to do that.

34
00:02:08,009 --> 00:02:11,850
And we saw that the most
common tokenization algorithm

35
00:02:11,850 --> 00:02:15,930
is the subword level tokenizer.

36
00:02:15,930 --> 00:02:18,290
And we saw that some
of the advantages

37
00:02:18,290 --> 00:02:26,230
were that roots of words
could be reused and leveraged,

38
00:02:26,230 --> 00:02:30,490
especially when it came to
representing those tokens.

39
00:02:30,490 --> 00:02:35,690
And speaking of
representation, once we

40
00:02:35,690 --> 00:02:40,810
were able to divide the input
text into atomic units, a.k.a.

41
00:02:40,810 --> 00:02:45,730
tokens, the next step
for us was to learn how

42
00:02:45,730 --> 00:02:48,690
to represent these embeddings.

43
00:02:48,690 --> 00:02:51,410
So if you remember, we
saw some methods that

44
00:02:51,410 --> 00:02:53,370
were very popular back then.

45
00:02:53,370 --> 00:02:56,730
So one of them was
called word2vec.

46
00:02:56,730 --> 00:03:01,130
And the representation was
learned from a proxy task, which

47
00:03:01,130 --> 00:03:05,130
was something like
predicting the center word

48
00:03:05,130 --> 00:03:08,970
or predicting the context words.

49
00:03:08,970 --> 00:03:13,090
But then we saw that this way
of learning representations

50
00:03:13,090 --> 00:03:15,970
had some limitations,
one of which

51
00:03:15,970 --> 00:03:21,410
was that these representations
were not context aware, meaning

52
00:03:21,410 --> 00:03:25,170
that if a word is
in a given sentence

53
00:03:25,170 --> 00:03:30,570
or in another sentence,
that word will

54
00:03:30,570 --> 00:03:34,410
have the same representation
in both sentences.

55
00:03:34,410 --> 00:03:38,610
And so for that reason, we saw
some other methods that were

56
00:03:38,610 --> 00:03:45,370
popular in the 2010s, one of
which was RNNs, if you remember.

57
00:03:45,370 --> 00:03:49,930
So RNNs had this
recurrent structure,

58
00:03:49,930 --> 00:03:52,850
which processed
tokens one at a time

59
00:03:52,850 --> 00:03:55,180
and kept an internal
representation

60
00:03:55,180 --> 00:03:57,980
of the sequence so far.

61
00:03:57,980 --> 00:04:00,260
But then we saw that
a big limitation

62
00:04:00,260 --> 00:04:04,140
of this problem of
long range dependency,

63
00:04:04,140 --> 00:04:07,220
and in particular,
the fact that tokens

64
00:04:07,220 --> 00:04:10,020
that were encoded
far in the past

65
00:04:10,020 --> 00:04:14,960
were not quantities that
were able to be kept I guess,

66
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:18,100
as the sequence got longer.

67
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:20,899
And this is the
reason why we saw

68
00:04:20,899 --> 00:04:23,100
the central idea of
this whole class, which

69
00:04:23,100 --> 00:04:30,340
is the idea of self-attention,
where tokens can actually attend

70
00:04:30,340 --> 00:04:33,140
to one another
regardless of where they

71
00:04:33,140 --> 00:04:35,240
are placed in the sequence.

72
00:04:35,240 --> 00:04:39,540
So you can think of
this as a direct link.

73
00:04:39,540 --> 00:04:43,280
And so this, for
instance, is what we saw.

74
00:04:43,280 --> 00:04:48,600
We saw that there are three main
terminologies that people use.

75
00:04:48,600 --> 00:04:51,320
So query, key, and value.

76
00:04:51,320 --> 00:04:55,740
So typically want to
how similar a query

77
00:04:55,740 --> 00:04:59,940
is compared to the
keys in the sequence.

78
00:04:59,940 --> 00:05:05,420
And you quantify that by
taking some dot products that's

79
00:05:05,420 --> 00:05:08,220
kind of scaled and softmax.

80
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:11,020
And then you have the
corresponding value

81
00:05:11,020 --> 00:05:11,880
that is taken.

82
00:05:11,880 --> 00:05:15,660
So at the end of the
day, we obtain some kind

83
00:05:15,660 --> 00:05:22,740
of weighted average of all the
tokens that are in the sequence.

84
00:05:22,740 --> 00:05:26,440
And then you may also be
familiar now with this formula.

85
00:05:26,440 --> 00:05:33,300
So softmax of qk transpose over
square root of k times v. So

86
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:39,120
this is the matrix formulation
of what I mentioned here,

87
00:05:39,120 --> 00:05:42,940
which is able to process
these computations in a very

88
00:05:42,940 --> 00:05:44,220
efficient way.

89
00:05:44,220 --> 00:05:50,300
And it's something that today's
hardware is well equipped to do.

90
00:05:50,300 --> 00:05:53,020
And then we finished
the first lecture

91
00:05:53,020 --> 00:05:55,580
by going through the
architecture that

92
00:05:55,580 --> 00:06:01,180
is the foundation of modern day
LLMs, which is the transformer.

93
00:06:01,180 --> 00:06:05,980
And we saw that there
are two notable parts

94
00:06:05,980 --> 00:06:07,120
in the transformer.

95
00:06:07,120 --> 00:06:12,640
So one was the encoder in
the left part of the figure.

96
00:06:12,640 --> 00:06:15,060
And then the right
part is the decoder.

97
00:06:15,060 --> 00:06:20,700
And we saw how this was applied
in the case of translation.

98
00:06:20,700 --> 00:06:23,280
So at the end of
the first lecture,

99
00:06:23,280 --> 00:06:30,980
we saw what motivated us to
end up with the transformer.

100
00:06:30,980 --> 00:06:33,900
And we saw that transformer
was working quite well

101
00:06:33,900 --> 00:06:36,160
in the case of translation.

102
00:06:36,160 --> 00:06:37,980
And so in the next
lecture, what we

103
00:06:37,980 --> 00:06:43,020
saw what were the
little improvements

104
00:06:43,020 --> 00:06:45,820
that people have made
to this architecture

105
00:06:45,820 --> 00:06:46,835
since it was released.

106
00:06:46,835 --> 00:06:48,210
And if you remember,
it remember,

107
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:53,190
it was in 2017 that
it was published.

108
00:06:53,190 --> 00:06:57,510
So one particular improvement
that people have made

109
00:06:57,510 --> 00:07:03,470
is in the way we
consider positions,

110
00:07:03,470 --> 00:07:06,630
because in the original
transformer, paper,

111
00:07:06,630 --> 00:07:10,810
positions were encoded
in an absolute way,

112
00:07:10,810 --> 00:07:16,510
as in each position
had its own embedding.

113
00:07:16,510 --> 00:07:21,910
And this embedding was added
to the token embedding.

114
00:07:21,910 --> 00:07:26,790
But then if we think about
it, positions, actually, we

115
00:07:26,790 --> 00:07:29,890
don't really care about
the absolute position.

116
00:07:29,890 --> 00:07:34,870
We care about the relative
position between tokens.

117
00:07:34,870 --> 00:07:37,470
And in particular,
we care about how far

118
00:07:37,470 --> 00:07:41,870
tokens are in the self-attention
computation, which

119
00:07:41,870 --> 00:07:45,350
is why we saw this method
that is now quite popular

120
00:07:45,350 --> 00:07:50,230
called rotary position
embeddings, a.k.a., rope

121
00:07:50,230 --> 00:07:51,750
that is now quite used.

122
00:07:51,750 --> 00:07:59,910
And it is a method that rotates
query and keys, both of which

123
00:07:59,910 --> 00:08:03,270
happen in the
self-attention computation.

124
00:08:03,270 --> 00:08:08,470
And so here what
is quantified here

125
00:08:08,470 --> 00:08:11,870
is purely a function of
the relative distance

126
00:08:11,870 --> 00:08:15,110
between two tokens.

127
00:08:15,110 --> 00:08:17,270
And not only that,
it is something

128
00:08:17,270 --> 00:08:21,750
that is taken care of in the
self-attention layer, which

129
00:08:21,750 --> 00:08:24,590
is what we care about.

130
00:08:24,590 --> 00:08:26,570
So this was one big improvement.

131
00:08:26,570 --> 00:08:29,630
And then we saw some other
improvements, especially when

132
00:08:29,630 --> 00:08:34,070
it came to how the
multi-head attention

133
00:08:34,070 --> 00:08:38,070
layer-- multi-head attention
layer was composed of.

134
00:08:38,070 --> 00:08:40,750
And in particular, we
saw that it was possible

135
00:08:40,750 --> 00:08:46,910
for us to have some groupings
of the matrices that we learn.

136
00:08:46,910 --> 00:08:50,950
So we don't need to have
one matrix, one projection

137
00:08:50,950 --> 00:08:56,350
matrix per head for, let's
say, keys and values.

138
00:08:56,350 --> 00:08:59,630
We can actually group them.

139
00:08:59,630 --> 00:09:02,250
So this is for instance,
what is mentioned here.

140
00:09:02,250 --> 00:09:05,150
So group query attention.

141
00:09:05,150 --> 00:09:07,830
And then we also saw
some other techniques

142
00:09:07,830 --> 00:09:09,570
that I have not
represented here,

143
00:09:09,570 --> 00:09:14,390
for instance, the normalization
layer in the transformer which

144
00:09:14,390 --> 00:09:19,010
here happens after
each sublayer.

145
00:09:19,010 --> 00:09:23,710
But I guess nowadays people have
tried moving the normalization

146
00:09:23,710 --> 00:09:26,170
piece before the sublayer.

147
00:09:26,170 --> 00:09:29,770
So here it's the
post-norm version.

148
00:09:29,770 --> 00:09:32,150
And then before
the sublayer part

149
00:09:32,150 --> 00:09:37,270
is called the pre-norm version.

150
00:09:37,270 --> 00:09:38,950
And then the last
thing that we saw

151
00:09:38,950 --> 00:09:43,440
was that from this transformer
former architecture,

152
00:09:43,440 --> 00:09:45,760
there are a lot
of derived models

153
00:09:45,760 --> 00:09:48,440
that were based from that.

154
00:09:48,440 --> 00:09:53,560
So we saw that if we only
keep the encoder part,

155
00:09:53,560 --> 00:09:57,280
we could compute very
meaningful embeddings.

156
00:09:57,280 --> 00:10:00,080
If you remember,
there was this kind

157
00:10:00,080 --> 00:10:04,080
of landmark paper on
encoder only model, which

158
00:10:04,080 --> 00:10:08,960
is BERT, which was heavily used
in the context of classification

159
00:10:08,960 --> 00:10:14,220
because it relied on the encoder
embedding of the CLS token.

160
00:10:14,220 --> 00:10:16,280
So that was one.

161
00:10:16,280 --> 00:10:18,000
But then we also
saw that there was

162
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:22,440
a number of other kinds of
models, all more or less derived

163
00:10:22,440 --> 00:10:23,740
from the transformer.

164
00:10:23,740 --> 00:10:27,160
So you could only keep the
encoder, which was for BERT.

165
00:10:27,160 --> 00:10:31,920
You could only keep the decoder
just, for instance, for GPT.

166
00:10:31,920 --> 00:10:35,840
And you could also
have both, which is

167
00:10:35,840 --> 00:10:39,320
for instance, the case of T5.

168
00:10:39,320 --> 00:10:43,960
And one particular aspect
of each of these models

169
00:10:43,960 --> 00:10:48,560
is that encoder only is
not able-- in the way

170
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:52,560
that we saw-- is not
able to generate text,

171
00:10:52,560 --> 00:10:54,960
but it's able to generate
embeddings which can

172
00:10:54,960 --> 00:10:57,000
be used for downstream tasks.

173
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:00,480
But then encoder
decoder models like T5

174
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:04,600
or decoder only
models like GPT, they

175
00:11:04,600 --> 00:11:10,160
can be autoregressive
and generate texts.

176
00:11:10,160 --> 00:11:13,780
The paradigm can be
text in, text out.

177
00:11:16,320 --> 00:11:21,920
And with that, we then focused
on what now everyone calls

178
00:11:21,920 --> 00:11:25,800
large language models,
which are transformer

179
00:11:25,800 --> 00:11:30,160
based models, specifically
text to text models.

180
00:11:30,160 --> 00:11:35,520
So decoder only
transformer based models.

181
00:11:35,520 --> 00:11:39,170
And we saw that people have
come up with a lot of new tricks

182
00:11:39,170 --> 00:11:43,930
now because these models,
as the name indicates,

183
00:11:43,930 --> 00:11:46,610
people have scaled them up.

184
00:11:46,610 --> 00:11:52,310
But then one question
was kind of thrown,

185
00:11:52,310 --> 00:11:58,610
which is do you actually need
all these parameters to just do

186
00:11:58,610 --> 00:12:00,930
a forward pass.

187
00:12:00,930 --> 00:12:05,290
So we saw one kind
of variant which was

188
00:12:05,290 --> 00:12:09,570
based on a mixture of experts.

189
00:12:09,570 --> 00:12:15,050
So what mixture of experts are
is instead of running everything

190
00:12:15,050 --> 00:12:17,970
through the whole
entire model, you're

191
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:22,250
going to instead have
a number of experts

192
00:12:22,250 --> 00:12:27,090
that you're going to
activate in a sparse way.

193
00:12:27,090 --> 00:12:28,890
So for instance, for
one input, you're

194
00:12:28,890 --> 00:12:31,515
going to just activate
just a subset.

195
00:12:31,515 --> 00:12:32,890
And then for
another input you're

196
00:12:32,890 --> 00:12:35,610
going to activate
another subset so

197
00:12:35,610 --> 00:12:40,930
that you don't need to do all
the computations all the time.

198
00:12:40,930 --> 00:12:44,730
And we saw that this
mixture of experts, they

199
00:12:44,730 --> 00:12:49,410
were used in LLMs, in particular
in the feedforward neural

200
00:12:49,410 --> 00:12:51,290
network layer.

201
00:12:51,290 --> 00:12:54,690
So here you would
have experts as being

202
00:12:54,690 --> 00:12:56,970
different feedforward
neural networks.

203
00:12:56,970 --> 00:13:00,170
And you would have
a gating mechanism

204
00:13:00,170 --> 00:13:03,970
that would reroute to
the correct feedforward

205
00:13:03,970 --> 00:13:07,250
neural network.

206
00:13:07,250 --> 00:13:10,810
And then we also saw that
some papers were also

207
00:13:10,810 --> 00:13:15,990
able to produce some nice
visualization in terms, I guess,

208
00:13:15,990 --> 00:13:20,390
which token gets routed to which
expert, because this routing,

209
00:13:20,390 --> 00:13:24,730
we saw that it was done
at the token level.

210
00:13:24,730 --> 00:13:27,090
And so one reason why it's
done at the token level

211
00:13:27,090 --> 00:13:30,850
is to be able to, I
guess, smartly put

212
00:13:30,850 --> 00:13:34,810
the experts on different pieces
of hardware, different GPUs,

213
00:13:34,810 --> 00:13:38,030
and then parallelize the
computation a little bit more.

214
00:13:40,810 --> 00:13:45,930
And then we also
saw that these LLMs,

215
00:13:45,930 --> 00:13:49,850
they always are tasked with
predicting the next token.

216
00:13:49,850 --> 00:13:52,490
And in order to
predict the next token

217
00:13:52,490 --> 00:13:57,230
we were interested in, I
guess, how we were doing this.

218
00:13:57,230 --> 00:14:03,250
And so one particular method
that people use is just sample.

219
00:14:03,250 --> 00:14:05,070
Sample from the
output distribution.

220
00:14:05,070 --> 00:14:07,090
So you have let's
say given an input

221
00:14:07,090 --> 00:14:11,210
you have a distribution
of probabilities of what

222
00:14:11,210 --> 00:14:13,910
the next token would be.

223
00:14:13,910 --> 00:14:16,330
That is output by the model.

224
00:14:16,330 --> 00:14:19,330
And what you do is
instead of let's

225
00:14:19,330 --> 00:14:21,690
say taking the highest
probability, which

226
00:14:21,690 --> 00:14:30,010
is called the greedy kind of
decoding, you actually sample.

227
00:14:30,010 --> 00:14:34,140
So it introduces some
randomness and allows the model

228
00:14:34,140 --> 00:14:39,460
to produce kind of a bigger
variety of kinds of outputs.

229
00:14:39,460 --> 00:14:46,280
And we saw that you could
adjust how much, I guess,

230
00:14:46,280 --> 00:14:49,300
a variety you want in
your outputs by tweaking

231
00:14:49,300 --> 00:14:52,740
a hyperparameter
called temperature.

232
00:14:52,740 --> 00:14:56,000
So very low temperature leads
to very spiky distribution.

233
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:00,020
So more deterministic outputs
and higher temperatures

234
00:15:00,020 --> 00:15:04,280
are, I guess, a bit more
random, a bit more creative.

235
00:15:07,020 --> 00:15:11,740
So until then, we
saw what LLMs were,

236
00:15:11,740 --> 00:15:14,620
how they were based on the
transformer, how they connected

237
00:15:14,620 --> 00:15:18,120
to the architecture that we
saw in the first lecture.

238
00:15:18,120 --> 00:15:22,580
And then in lecture 4, we
saw how people actually

239
00:15:22,580 --> 00:15:30,100
trained those LLMs because as I
mentioned, these LLMs are large.

240
00:15:30,100 --> 00:15:35,440
And so you cannot naively
fit them in your hardware.

241
00:15:35,440 --> 00:15:38,420
You need to be a little
bit smart about it.

242
00:15:38,420 --> 00:15:44,420
So in particular, what people
have noticed in the early 2020s

243
00:15:44,420 --> 00:15:51,100
is that the bigger your model
is, the better your performance.

244
00:15:51,100 --> 00:15:53,620
And so people just
started building

245
00:15:53,620 --> 00:15:54,960
bigger and bigger models.

246
00:15:54,960 --> 00:16:00,220
So here in the illustration
we saw that-- so on the y-axis

247
00:16:00,220 --> 00:16:01,820
is the Teslas.

248
00:16:01,820 --> 00:16:04,060
So the lower the better.

249
00:16:04,060 --> 00:16:11,220
So we saw that the more compute
you use, the better your test

250
00:16:11,220 --> 00:16:12,280
performance.

251
00:16:12,280 --> 00:16:16,900
And same with increasing
the data set size.

252
00:16:16,900 --> 00:16:20,980
And same with increasing
the number of parameters.

253
00:16:20,980 --> 00:16:25,140
But then as you know
compute is not infinite.

254
00:16:25,140 --> 00:16:27,580
So there was a
natural question that

255
00:16:27,580 --> 00:16:32,750
came out of the community which
was if we give you a given

256
00:16:32,750 --> 00:16:40,310
budget, a given compute budget,
can you choose, I guess some,

257
00:16:40,310 --> 00:16:46,590
quote unquote, optimal
number of parameters and data

258
00:16:46,590 --> 00:16:50,590
set size on which you
want to train your model.

259
00:16:50,590 --> 00:16:55,230
And so we saw that there was
this paper that was published

260
00:16:55,230 --> 00:16:59,590
in the early 2020s,
which actually studied

261
00:16:59,590 --> 00:17:02,830
the relationship
between, I guess,

262
00:17:02,830 --> 00:17:08,390
if you vary the data set size
and the size of your model

263
00:17:08,390 --> 00:17:12,470
and the performance
on the test set.

264
00:17:12,470 --> 00:17:15,869
And then we saw that actually,
most models at the time

265
00:17:15,869 --> 00:17:18,710
were what we say
undertrained because they

266
00:17:18,710 --> 00:17:21,670
were too big compared
to the data set

267
00:17:21,670 --> 00:17:22,970
that they were trained on.

268
00:17:22,970 --> 00:17:24,553
The data set that
they were trained on

269
00:17:24,553 --> 00:17:27,950
was not as big as
they should have been.

270
00:17:27,950 --> 00:17:30,550
And so in particular, there
was a kind of a rule of thumb

271
00:17:30,550 --> 00:17:35,310
that came out of this, which
was if you have a given

272
00:17:35,310 --> 00:17:38,590
number of parameters
in your model,

273
00:17:38,590 --> 00:17:42,670
you should at least train
it on 20 times the number

274
00:17:42,670 --> 00:17:45,950
of parameters in
terms of tokens.

275
00:17:45,950 --> 00:17:50,250
So for instance, if you have
a 100 billion parameter model,

276
00:17:50,250 --> 00:17:55,550
you should train it on at
least 2 trillion tokens

277
00:17:55,550 --> 00:17:59,630
because the 2 trillion
is 100 billion times 20.

278
00:17:59,630 --> 00:18:04,190
So that's the rule of thumb
that people have used.

279
00:18:04,190 --> 00:18:06,790
And then as I
mentioned previously,

280
00:18:06,790 --> 00:18:08,670
these models are huge.

281
00:18:08,670 --> 00:18:11,910
So people have
tried to also make

282
00:18:11,910 --> 00:18:15,110
the computation more efficient.

283
00:18:15,110 --> 00:18:17,735
And so there was this
method that we saw,

284
00:18:17,735 --> 00:18:19,110
which is actually
quite important

285
00:18:19,110 --> 00:18:22,790
called flash attention.

286
00:18:22,790 --> 00:18:25,990
And flash attention
is a method it

287
00:18:25,990 --> 00:18:31,750
that leverages the strength
of the underlying hardware.

288
00:18:31,750 --> 00:18:35,590
And in particular, it
looks at-- so GPUs, more

289
00:18:35,590 --> 00:18:39,750
particularly-- it looks
at the kinds of memories

290
00:18:39,750 --> 00:18:42,470
that a GPU has.

291
00:18:42,470 --> 00:18:49,570
So it has a big, but slow memory
and a small, but fast memory.

292
00:18:49,570 --> 00:18:53,390
So the HBM and
SRAM respectively.

293
00:18:53,390 --> 00:18:57,350
And we saw that
this method tries

294
00:18:57,350 --> 00:19:02,790
to minimize the number of reads
and writes to the big and slow

295
00:19:02,790 --> 00:19:05,090
memory, to the HBM.

296
00:19:05,090 --> 00:19:08,870
And so the way it
was doing this was

297
00:19:08,870 --> 00:19:14,110
to divide the computation
in little bits

298
00:19:14,110 --> 00:19:17,190
that it would send
to the SRAM, which

299
00:19:17,190 --> 00:19:22,230
is the small but fast memory,
so that it can do the end

300
00:19:22,230 --> 00:19:25,240
to end computation
and then send it

301
00:19:25,240 --> 00:19:28,840
back to where it was in order
to do the full end to end

302
00:19:28,840 --> 00:19:31,720
computation.

303
00:19:31,720 --> 00:19:34,260
So that method is
an exact method,

304
00:19:34,260 --> 00:19:39,160
meaning that we're not doing any
approximations to the results.

305
00:19:39,160 --> 00:19:42,080
But it led to
significant speedups.

306
00:19:42,080 --> 00:19:44,360
And in particular, there
was this second idea

307
00:19:44,360 --> 00:19:47,600
from the paper, which is
a kind of an important one

308
00:19:47,600 --> 00:19:52,560
as well, which was that
sometimes it's OK for you

309
00:19:52,560 --> 00:19:56,200
to not store results.

310
00:19:56,200 --> 00:20:00,040
It's OK for you to just throw
them out and then recompute

311
00:20:00,040 --> 00:20:02,520
when you need them again.

312
00:20:02,520 --> 00:20:05,240
So there is this
idea of computation

313
00:20:05,240 --> 00:20:11,200
using what I described,
which led to faster runtimes,

314
00:20:11,200 --> 00:20:16,320
even though we were
doing more computations.

315
00:20:16,320 --> 00:20:18,480
So that was flash attention.

316
00:20:18,480 --> 00:20:23,120
And we also saw a
number of other methods

317
00:20:23,120 --> 00:20:27,900
that were meant to, I guess,
parallelize the computation.

318
00:20:27,900 --> 00:20:31,760
So we saw data
parallelism, which

319
00:20:31,760 --> 00:20:36,440
was this idea of not having
all your data be processed

320
00:20:36,440 --> 00:20:43,640
on a single GPU, but instead
divide it into multiple places.

321
00:20:43,640 --> 00:20:45,380
And then we had
the second method,

322
00:20:45,380 --> 00:20:51,160
which was model parallelism,
where even for a given forward

323
00:20:51,160 --> 00:20:56,760
pass, you would actually
involve multiple GPUs.

324
00:20:56,760 --> 00:20:59,820
So anyway, there were a lot of
very interesting techniques,

325
00:20:59,820 --> 00:21:04,440
a lot of different
ideas about how to train

326
00:21:04,440 --> 00:21:08,000
this model in an efficient way.

327
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:11,840
And in particular, so
what I described here

328
00:21:11,840 --> 00:21:16,800
is mostly important for the
first step of the training

329
00:21:16,800 --> 00:21:21,080
process of an LLM, which is
called the pre-training, which

330
00:21:21,080 --> 00:21:26,680
is meant to teach the model
about the structure of language

331
00:21:26,680 --> 00:21:29,680
about the structure of codes.

332
00:21:29,680 --> 00:21:31,640
And in particular,
this model was trained

333
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:33,940
with huge amounts of data.

334
00:21:33,940 --> 00:21:37,920
So think about
trillions of tokens

335
00:21:37,920 --> 00:21:41,640
or even tens of
trillions of tokens.

336
00:21:41,640 --> 00:21:45,760
And so that first step goes
from an initialized model

337
00:21:45,760 --> 00:21:49,520
to a model that is
able to autocomplete

338
00:21:49,520 --> 00:21:53,480
because it is trained with
an objective of predicting

339
00:21:53,480 --> 00:21:56,200
the next token.

340
00:21:56,200 --> 00:21:59,600
So at the end of
this first stage,

341
00:21:59,600 --> 00:22:02,980
you have a model that
knows how to autocomplete,

342
00:22:02,980 --> 00:22:07,600
but you have a model that is
not very helpful because it only

343
00:22:07,600 --> 00:22:11,080
knows how to complete things.

344
00:22:11,080 --> 00:22:17,200
So in order to have the model
be useful for our use cases,

345
00:22:17,200 --> 00:22:20,490
we had this second step, which
is called the fine tuning

346
00:22:20,490 --> 00:22:25,890
step, where we teach
the model on the kinds

347
00:22:25,890 --> 00:22:30,410
of input/output pairs that
we wanted to perform well.

348
00:22:30,410 --> 00:22:35,170
So this is also called the
SFT stage supervised fine

349
00:22:35,170 --> 00:22:36,850
tuning stage.

350
00:22:36,850 --> 00:22:39,650
And at the end of
this second step,

351
00:22:39,650 --> 00:22:45,210
we have a model that not only
knows the structure of text

352
00:22:45,210 --> 00:22:50,410
and codes, but also is able
to behave in the way you want.

353
00:22:50,410 --> 00:22:54,890
But so far, up
until step number 2,

354
00:22:54,890 --> 00:22:59,690
we have only taught
our model what to do.

355
00:22:59,690 --> 00:23:03,530
We have not taught
it what to not do.

356
00:23:03,530 --> 00:23:07,330
And this is why we had our third
step, which was the preference

357
00:23:07,330 --> 00:23:11,610
tuning step, where we
took our model that

358
00:23:11,610 --> 00:23:13,330
went through the
pre-training stage, that

359
00:23:13,330 --> 00:23:14,830
went to the SFT stage.

360
00:23:14,830 --> 00:23:18,970
And now we want to inject
some negative signal

361
00:23:18,970 --> 00:23:23,890
as well as in I want
you to prefer this

362
00:23:23,890 --> 00:23:26,530
compared to this output.

363
00:23:26,530 --> 00:23:31,790
And this third step
uses preference data.

364
00:23:31,790 --> 00:23:35,770
So like the name suggests,
so preference tuning uses

365
00:23:35,770 --> 00:23:40,130
preference data which is
typically pairwise data where

366
00:23:40,130 --> 00:23:46,210
humans say I prefer this
output compared to that output.

367
00:23:46,210 --> 00:23:51,090
And typically, the model here is
able to align the kind of output

368
00:23:51,090 --> 00:23:53,530
it produces with
human preferences that

369
00:23:53,530 --> 00:23:57,990
could be along the
dimension of usefulness,

370
00:23:57,990 --> 00:24:01,483
of safety, friendliness, tone.

371
00:24:01,483 --> 00:24:03,150
There's a bunch of
different dimensions.

372
00:24:03,150 --> 00:24:08,530
But yeah, so that's what is
happening in this third step.

373
00:24:08,530 --> 00:24:12,330
And in this third step,
it's actually in lecture 5

374
00:24:12,330 --> 00:24:18,140
that we dug into what
that third step was about.

375
00:24:18,140 --> 00:24:24,820
So if you remember, we had
drawn a parallel between the way

376
00:24:24,820 --> 00:24:27,540
our LLM produces tokens.

377
00:24:27,540 --> 00:24:33,380
And I guess what people in the
reinforcement learning field,

378
00:24:33,380 --> 00:24:39,300
I guess, consider how a
given policy is interacting

379
00:24:39,300 --> 00:24:42,140
with some environments
and performing some action

380
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:44,380
and being in some states.

381
00:24:44,380 --> 00:24:47,140
And the reason why
we drew that parallel

382
00:24:47,140 --> 00:24:53,100
was to be able to leverage some
RL-based techniques in order

383
00:24:53,100 --> 00:24:54,740
to train our model.

384
00:24:54,740 --> 00:25:00,260
So in this case, we said our LLM
is a little bit like a policy.

385
00:25:00,260 --> 00:25:03,140
So given some state,
which is the input

386
00:25:03,140 --> 00:25:08,640
it has received so far, it
can perform the next action.

387
00:25:08,640 --> 00:25:13,060
And in this case, it is
to predict the next token.

388
00:25:13,060 --> 00:25:20,140
And this prediction is made
in the environment of tokens.

389
00:25:20,140 --> 00:25:25,780
And when we predict a
completion, what we do

390
00:25:25,780 --> 00:25:30,500
is, at the end of the day, we
have some signal, some reward,

391
00:25:30,500 --> 00:25:34,380
which can be the
human preference.

392
00:25:34,380 --> 00:25:38,100
So this is the parallel
we drew with the RL world.

393
00:25:38,100 --> 00:25:41,660
And with that in mind,
we talked about rewards.

394
00:25:41,660 --> 00:25:43,860
But the problem is
that rewards are

395
00:25:43,860 --> 00:25:48,660
only available for a limited
set of data, which is why

396
00:25:48,660 --> 00:25:52,500
we saw how to model rewards.

397
00:25:52,500 --> 00:25:54,040
So we saw this formula.

398
00:25:54,040 --> 00:25:58,500
If you remember it's called
the Bradley-Terry formulation,

399
00:25:58,500 --> 00:26:06,240
which models how the probability
of an output being better.

400
00:26:06,240 --> 00:26:11,340
Another one is as a function
of, I guess, two scores,

401
00:26:11,340 --> 00:26:15,820
like the score of output I
and the score of output J.

402
00:26:15,820 --> 00:26:18,500
And we saw that
reward models, they

403
00:26:18,500 --> 00:26:23,140
are typically trained by
having this formulation in mind

404
00:26:23,140 --> 00:26:25,940
in a pairwise fashion.

405
00:26:25,940 --> 00:26:30,800
So what this means is a reward
model, you give it two outputs.

406
00:26:30,800 --> 00:26:33,900
You say this one is
good, this one is bad.

407
00:26:33,900 --> 00:26:36,940
And then I want you to
say this one is good.

408
00:26:36,940 --> 00:26:39,420
You train it in a
pairwise fashion.

409
00:26:39,420 --> 00:26:43,160
But then your model is actually
predicting always two scores.

410
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:45,660
It's always predicting
the score RI

411
00:26:45,660 --> 00:26:52,460
for output I, RJ for output
J. And so at inference time

412
00:26:52,460 --> 00:26:57,100
you're only giving
it one output.

413
00:26:57,100 --> 00:26:58,920
So I think that's one subtlety.

414
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:00,640
We train it in a pairwise way.

415
00:27:00,640 --> 00:27:06,960
But at inference time, we're
using it in an individual way,

416
00:27:06,960 --> 00:27:09,630
if that makes sense.

417
00:27:09,630 --> 00:27:12,870
And so once we trained
our reward model using

418
00:27:12,870 --> 00:27:16,750
this formulation, then
we were able to use

419
00:27:16,750 --> 00:27:23,390
it to steer our LLM towards the
direction that we care about.

420
00:27:23,390 --> 00:27:27,710
So if you remember, the
way we steer our LLM

421
00:27:27,710 --> 00:27:31,150
in the direction of
human preferences

422
00:27:31,150 --> 00:27:35,070
is to give it a
prompt so that it

423
00:27:35,070 --> 00:27:40,670
can produce a completion,
a.k.a., a rollout.

424
00:27:40,670 --> 00:27:44,750
Or in simpler terms, an answer.

425
00:27:44,750 --> 00:27:48,330
And then we take this
prompt, we take this answer.

426
00:27:48,330 --> 00:27:52,270
We put them both in the
reward model that tells us

427
00:27:52,270 --> 00:27:55,550
how good the model response is.

428
00:27:55,550 --> 00:27:58,270
And depending on what
the reward model says,

429
00:27:58,270 --> 00:28:02,230
we can tune the
weights of the LLM

430
00:28:02,230 --> 00:28:06,410
in a way that maximizes human
or the reward that we saw,

431
00:28:06,410 --> 00:28:10,910
which is trained on
human preferences.

432
00:28:10,910 --> 00:28:17,950
And the last function
of this RL setup

433
00:28:17,950 --> 00:28:20,550
is typically
something that tries

434
00:28:20,550 --> 00:28:27,790
to maximize rewards, but also
keep the model close to the base

435
00:28:27,790 --> 00:28:28,410
model.

436
00:28:28,410 --> 00:28:32,190
And here, by base model,
we mean the SFT model.

437
00:28:32,190 --> 00:28:35,710
And the reason why we want
that is because this reward

438
00:28:35,710 --> 00:28:37,630
is imperfect.

439
00:28:37,630 --> 00:28:41,710
So we saw this phenomenon
of reward hacking

440
00:28:41,710 --> 00:28:45,070
where your reward
can be imperfect.

441
00:28:45,070 --> 00:28:49,990
And the LLM can exploit
its imperfect nature

442
00:28:49,990 --> 00:28:52,630
to tune it in a way that
actually does not align

443
00:28:52,630 --> 00:28:54,910
with what you want it to be.

444
00:28:54,910 --> 00:28:57,550
So you want the LLM
to not be too far

445
00:28:57,550 --> 00:29:02,510
from the base model, which is
actually already a good model.

446
00:29:02,510 --> 00:29:05,830
So it's a way to regularize
that if you want.

447
00:29:05,830 --> 00:29:11,390
And you also want
the iteration updates

448
00:29:11,390 --> 00:29:15,230
to not be too big either.

449
00:29:15,230 --> 00:29:17,553
So you typically have
these two constraints.

450
00:29:17,553 --> 00:29:19,970
You don't want it to deviate
too much from the base model,

451
00:29:19,970 --> 00:29:23,470
but you don't want it to deviate
too much from the previous RL

452
00:29:23,470 --> 00:29:25,470
iteration.

453
00:29:25,470 --> 00:29:27,030
And then just as a
reminder, I think

454
00:29:27,030 --> 00:29:31,190
this was lecture 5 I think was
the most technically challenging

455
00:29:31,190 --> 00:29:33,610
of the whole class.

456
00:29:33,610 --> 00:29:35,230
So completely fine
if the first time

457
00:29:35,230 --> 00:29:37,670
you were like, what's happening.

458
00:29:37,670 --> 00:29:42,970
But hopefully now, it should
be a little bit more clear.

459
00:29:42,970 --> 00:29:43,470
Cool.

460
00:29:43,470 --> 00:29:45,410
And then after lecture
5, we're like, OK,

461
00:29:45,410 --> 00:29:47,790
we've done a lot of hard work.

462
00:29:47,790 --> 00:29:51,450
So the good thing
is we're in 2025.

463
00:29:51,450 --> 00:29:56,750
And in the past 12
months, or now 14 months,

464
00:29:56,750 --> 00:29:59,470
we've seen a lot
of models that were

465
00:29:59,470 --> 00:30:03,110
being released with these
reasoning capabilities.

466
00:30:03,110 --> 00:30:09,080
And the way they were trained to
exhibit these advanced reasoning

467
00:30:09,080 --> 00:30:12,360
capabilities was
actually leveraging

468
00:30:12,360 --> 00:30:16,360
a lot of the techniques
that we saw in lecture 5,

469
00:30:16,360 --> 00:30:19,240
just like RL based techniques.

470
00:30:19,240 --> 00:30:23,200
And in particular, what
we want our LLM to do

471
00:30:23,200 --> 00:30:29,120
is to output a reasoning
chain before producing

472
00:30:29,120 --> 00:30:31,960
the final answer.

473
00:30:31,960 --> 00:30:33,760
And the reason why
we wanted to do that

474
00:30:33,760 --> 00:30:37,360
is because people have
seen that it improves

475
00:30:37,360 --> 00:30:39,200
the performance of the model.

476
00:30:39,200 --> 00:30:44,160
And so it's actually relying on
this idea of chain of thoughts,

477
00:30:44,160 --> 00:30:47,680
which I believe we saw
at lecture 3, which

478
00:30:47,680 --> 00:30:52,640
is a prompting technique to have
your model output the reasoning

479
00:30:52,640 --> 00:30:55,880
before outputting the response.

480
00:30:55,880 --> 00:31:00,560
So long story short, up
until lecture 6 our LLM

481
00:31:00,560 --> 00:31:05,560
was having a prompt as input,
directly outputting the output.

482
00:31:05,560 --> 00:31:07,760
But in lecture 7, we said--

483
00:31:07,760 --> 00:31:11,240
sorry, in lecture
6 we said, well,

484
00:31:11,240 --> 00:31:14,760
let's have our LLM
actually first output

485
00:31:14,760 --> 00:31:17,960
a reasoning chain that
the user may or may not

486
00:31:17,960 --> 00:31:23,560
have access to before
outputting the final answer.

487
00:31:23,560 --> 00:31:26,500
So you want to teach
the LLM to do that.

488
00:31:26,500 --> 00:31:27,880
So how do you do that?

489
00:31:27,880 --> 00:31:30,440
Well, first before
doing this, I just

490
00:31:30,440 --> 00:31:33,040
want to show you this
chart, which we saw,

491
00:31:33,040 --> 00:31:36,680
which is the
performance of the model

492
00:31:36,680 --> 00:31:42,480
as we're teaching it to
produce these reasoning chains.

493
00:31:42,480 --> 00:31:46,440
So people have typically
measured the improvement

494
00:31:46,440 --> 00:31:51,580
in performance by comparing it
to, I guess, certain benchmarks.

495
00:31:51,580 --> 00:31:55,180
And this one is a popular
one, the aim benchmark,

496
00:31:55,180 --> 00:31:58,000
which is a math benchmark.

497
00:31:58,000 --> 00:32:02,130
And we saw that as the
training progresses,

498
00:32:02,130 --> 00:32:05,490
the accuracy number
of guess what

499
00:32:05,490 --> 00:32:08,530
the LLM outputs is increasing.

500
00:32:08,530 --> 00:32:11,250
But back to what I was saying.

501
00:32:11,250 --> 00:32:17,290
The key technique that we
use to teach the model how

502
00:32:17,290 --> 00:32:24,250
to output these reasoning chains
is leveraging the RL techniques

503
00:32:24,250 --> 00:32:26,810
that we saw in lecture 5.

504
00:32:26,810 --> 00:32:31,010
And in particular,
up until now, we

505
00:32:31,010 --> 00:32:36,650
saw PPO was the main RL
algorithm that people were

506
00:32:36,650 --> 00:32:40,250
using up to maybe last year.

507
00:32:40,250 --> 00:32:45,410
And now people are kind
of prioritizing GRPO

508
00:32:45,410 --> 00:32:49,970
as an RL algorithm in order to
teach the model to be better

509
00:32:49,970 --> 00:32:52,410
at reasoning tasks.

510
00:32:52,410 --> 00:32:57,210
And there are several reasons to
that I will explicit right now.

511
00:32:57,210 --> 00:33:02,930
So we saw this illustration
that compared how

512
00:33:02,930 --> 00:33:06,970
GRPO was differing with PPO.

513
00:33:06,970 --> 00:33:09,490
And if you can see
in the graph, there

514
00:33:09,490 --> 00:33:12,210
are a few things
that are different.

515
00:33:12,210 --> 00:33:20,330
The first thing is that GRPO
does not rely on a value model.

516
00:33:20,330 --> 00:33:22,630
So who remembers what
the value model is?

517
00:33:28,950 --> 00:33:29,450
Yep.

518
00:33:35,490 --> 00:33:36,350
Yes, exactly.

519
00:33:36,350 --> 00:33:39,930
So the value function
is trying to predict

520
00:33:39,930 --> 00:33:44,170
what the reward would
be if you were to follow

521
00:33:44,170 --> 00:33:47,250
the policy of the LLM.

522
00:33:47,250 --> 00:33:54,690
And I guess it's a way to
have some baseline as to how

523
00:33:54,690 --> 00:33:58,050
good some predictions are.

524
00:33:58,050 --> 00:34:00,650
You want to make
it more relative.

525
00:34:00,650 --> 00:34:03,770
So the value function
is a way for us

526
00:34:03,770 --> 00:34:06,850
to make these rewards
a little bit more

527
00:34:06,850 --> 00:34:09,250
relative to one another.

528
00:34:09,250 --> 00:34:12,310
And so that's how
PPO was doing this.

529
00:34:12,310 --> 00:34:13,969
So it was having
a value model that

530
00:34:13,969 --> 00:34:17,350
was making these predictions.

531
00:34:17,350 --> 00:34:21,610
And then we had these
generalized advantage estimation

532
00:34:21,610 --> 00:34:27,290
method that was combining
the rewards predictions

533
00:34:27,290 --> 00:34:30,370
with the value
function predictions

534
00:34:30,370 --> 00:34:33,810
in order to have what
we call advantages.

535
00:34:33,810 --> 00:34:37,330
So advantages is how
good's your output

536
00:34:37,330 --> 00:34:40,810
is compared to some baseline.

537
00:34:40,810 --> 00:34:44,170
But then in contrast
to that, GRPO

538
00:34:44,170 --> 00:34:49,010
said, OK, today, we don't
need a value function

539
00:34:49,010 --> 00:34:53,170
because it's too expensive
to train to maintain

540
00:34:53,170 --> 00:34:55,980
what we're going to do instead.

541
00:34:55,980 --> 00:35:00,660
Is generate several
completions, and then

542
00:35:00,660 --> 00:35:09,340
have some formula that compares
the rewards of these completions

543
00:35:09,340 --> 00:35:12,300
to one another.

544
00:35:12,300 --> 00:35:17,780
So it's going to have some
relative effect in a sense

545
00:35:17,780 --> 00:35:21,940
that it will make
things more relative.

546
00:35:21,940 --> 00:35:29,780
And in doing so you're actually
not needed to maintain and train

547
00:35:29,780 --> 00:35:31,700
a value function.

548
00:35:31,700 --> 00:35:36,740
And that's one big
difference compared to PPO.

549
00:35:36,740 --> 00:35:39,660
And the second big
difference, which

550
00:35:39,660 --> 00:35:42,700
is not represented
in this illustration,

551
00:35:42,700 --> 00:35:46,620
is that GRPO is
typically an algorithm

552
00:35:46,620 --> 00:35:51,740
that people have used in the
context of teaching your model

553
00:35:51,740 --> 00:35:55,260
to be better at reasoning tasks.

554
00:35:55,260 --> 00:35:59,140
And so we saw that
these kinds of problems

555
00:35:59,140 --> 00:36:05,340
have a verifiable reward
because when you complete a math

556
00:36:05,340 --> 00:36:10,420
problem, you actually know
the answer you need to get to.

557
00:36:10,420 --> 00:36:13,700
So you don't need to train
a reward model to tell you

558
00:36:13,700 --> 00:36:16,420
how good your final answer
is, because you already

559
00:36:16,420 --> 00:36:19,020
know the answer.

560
00:36:19,020 --> 00:36:22,580
And so we saw that
GRPO was in particular

561
00:36:22,580 --> 00:36:25,980
used in the context of when
you actually don't even

562
00:36:25,980 --> 00:36:28,420
need reward model,
when you actually

563
00:36:28,420 --> 00:36:30,740
have a verifiable reward.

564
00:36:30,740 --> 00:36:35,820
So at the end of the day, the
only two models you need to keep

565
00:36:35,820 --> 00:36:39,900
are the policy model
and the reference model

566
00:36:39,900 --> 00:36:44,540
to be able to just compare how
far you are from the reference

567
00:36:44,540 --> 00:36:45,120
model.

568
00:36:49,460 --> 00:36:50,440
Cool?

569
00:36:50,440 --> 00:36:53,990
I know this one was also
a challenging class.

570
00:36:53,990 --> 00:36:55,990
I guess, so far so good.

571
00:36:55,990 --> 00:36:57,690
And this is also on the final.

572
00:36:57,690 --> 00:37:00,990
So which is why
I'm taking things

573
00:37:00,990 --> 00:37:05,390
more slowly for this
second part of the recap.

574
00:37:05,390 --> 00:37:08,270
So is everything good so far?

575
00:37:08,270 --> 00:37:10,410
Yeah?

576
00:37:10,410 --> 00:37:10,910
Perfect.

577
00:37:10,910 --> 00:37:13,650
We also saw some
extensions of GRPO.

578
00:37:13,650 --> 00:37:17,870
So if you remember, there
was some kind of bias

579
00:37:17,870 --> 00:37:27,550
that was a result of the
loss function of GRPO having

580
00:37:27,550 --> 00:37:33,870
some normalization term
that penalized tokens

581
00:37:33,870 --> 00:37:38,950
that were in shorter outputs.

582
00:37:38,950 --> 00:37:44,890
So we saw that if you use
GRPO in its original case,

583
00:37:44,890 --> 00:37:50,790
in its original form, we saw
that after a certain point,

584
00:37:50,790 --> 00:37:54,750
the algorithm will incentivize
your model to produce

585
00:37:54,750 --> 00:37:57,090
longer and longer answers.

586
00:37:57,090 --> 00:37:59,990
Longer and longer
incorrect answers.

587
00:37:59,990 --> 00:38:01,990
And the reason why
it does that is

588
00:38:01,990 --> 00:38:06,590
because relative to
short, incorrect answers,

589
00:38:06,590 --> 00:38:12,150
it penalizes less long
incorrect answers.

590
00:38:12,150 --> 00:38:14,950
And so this is the reason
why there are some extensions

591
00:38:14,950 --> 00:38:19,190
that people have worked
on this year, one of which

592
00:38:19,190 --> 00:38:21,970
was GRPO done right.

593
00:38:21,970 --> 00:38:26,790
So we saw that they basically
removed the normalization term.

594
00:38:26,790 --> 00:38:29,710
And there was another method
that we saw which was called

595
00:38:29,710 --> 00:38:34,250
DAPO, D-A-P-O, which
also had some variants.

596
00:38:36,950 --> 00:38:39,210
And that's for reasoning models.

597
00:38:39,210 --> 00:38:43,390
And then lecture
7, we had a model

598
00:38:43,390 --> 00:38:45,910
that we knew how to train it.

599
00:38:45,910 --> 00:38:51,170
We knew how to use it
for reasoning tasks,

600
00:38:51,170 --> 00:38:52,690
how to train it to be better.

601
00:38:52,690 --> 00:38:56,670
But now we wanted the model
to be useful and interacting

602
00:38:56,670 --> 00:39:01,030
with outside systems.

603
00:39:01,030 --> 00:39:06,310
So we saw one technique that is
kind of an essential technique

604
00:39:06,310 --> 00:39:11,950
called RAG, short for retrieval
augmented generation, that

605
00:39:11,950 --> 00:39:16,510
is meant for you
to be able to fetch

606
00:39:16,510 --> 00:39:20,630
relevant documents from
some knowledge base

607
00:39:20,630 --> 00:39:26,230
in order to answer a
question, or answer a prompt.

608
00:39:26,230 --> 00:39:28,910
And the reason why
you want to do that

609
00:39:28,910 --> 00:39:32,270
is that the
knowledge of your LLM

610
00:39:32,270 --> 00:39:41,350
is including up to the data that
is up to the knowledge cutoff

611
00:39:41,350 --> 00:39:46,600
date, which is the max dates of
what your LLM has been trained

612
00:39:46,600 --> 00:39:48,320
on.

613
00:39:48,320 --> 00:39:51,080
And from a practical
standpoint, I

614
00:39:51,080 --> 00:39:55,360
guess from what we see nowadays,
you're typically not training

615
00:39:55,360 --> 00:39:58,240
your LLM daily or continuously.

616
00:39:58,240 --> 00:40:01,400
And so in cases where
you need your LLM

617
00:40:01,400 --> 00:40:04,760
to about things that
happened recently

618
00:40:04,760 --> 00:40:07,280
or about things
that happened that

619
00:40:07,280 --> 00:40:12,360
were not in your
LLM training data.

620
00:40:12,360 --> 00:40:16,000
You want your LLM to have
access to such information.

621
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:21,040
And so that's how
RAG is very useful.

622
00:40:21,040 --> 00:40:24,000
So we saw that RAG
depended very heavily

623
00:40:24,000 --> 00:40:27,840
on the way it retrieves data.

624
00:40:27,840 --> 00:40:31,000
So we saw that the
retrieval part was mainly

625
00:40:31,000 --> 00:40:33,240
composed of two steps.

626
00:40:33,240 --> 00:40:38,600
So the first one was
candidate retrieval,

627
00:40:38,600 --> 00:40:43,720
which uses bye encoder
kind of setup where air.

628
00:40:43,720 --> 00:40:47,720
You're basically doing
some semantic search.

629
00:40:47,720 --> 00:40:50,340
So you're computing the
embedding of the query.

630
00:40:50,340 --> 00:40:52,960
You have some
pre-computed embeddings

631
00:40:52,960 --> 00:40:55,560
of the documents in
your knowledge base,

632
00:40:55,560 --> 00:41:00,500
and you're taking the ones that
maximize some similarity score.

633
00:41:00,500 --> 00:41:05,280
Let's say some
cosine similarity.

634
00:41:05,280 --> 00:41:10,380
So this first step is allowing
you to retrieve, I guess,

635
00:41:10,380 --> 00:41:14,960
a filtered version of
the potential documents.

636
00:41:14,960 --> 00:41:17,700
And then typically,
you have a second step,

637
00:41:17,700 --> 00:41:20,400
which is called ranking--

638
00:41:20,400 --> 00:41:22,880
or reranking because
the first step already

639
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:24,760
gives you a ranking--

640
00:41:24,760 --> 00:41:30,120
which has typically a
more sophisticated setup.

641
00:41:30,120 --> 00:41:36,520
So it's a cross encoder kind of
setup where you have your query

642
00:41:36,520 --> 00:41:41,040
and your document that
are both fed to some model

643
00:41:41,040 --> 00:41:45,520
and produces a
more precise score.

644
00:41:45,520 --> 00:41:50,800
And then you use this final
score to rank the final results.

645
00:41:50,800 --> 00:41:55,160
And you typically choose
the top, let's say, k.

646
00:41:55,160 --> 00:41:57,340
And then you add
them to your prompts.

647
00:41:57,340 --> 00:41:58,980
So it's the augmented part.

648
00:41:58,980 --> 00:42:02,040
So retrieval is everything
I mentioned so far.

649
00:42:02,040 --> 00:42:04,520
And then once you have
the relevant documents,

650
00:42:04,520 --> 00:42:08,480
you add them in your prompt,
which is the augmented part.

651
00:42:08,480 --> 00:42:12,000
And you generate the answer.

652
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:14,280
So the reason why I'm
taking so much time on RAG

653
00:42:14,280 --> 00:42:18,320
is RAG is such an
important concept.

654
00:42:18,320 --> 00:42:24,080
Also, if you were to
have interviews or also

655
00:42:24,080 --> 00:42:27,120
maybe in the exam who knows.

656
00:42:27,120 --> 00:42:30,960
So I think it's an important
concept to have in mind.

657
00:42:30,960 --> 00:42:35,240
The second one that we
saw was tool calling.

658
00:42:35,240 --> 00:42:45,130
And tool calling is allowing
your LLM to leverage tools.

659
00:42:45,130 --> 00:42:48,810
The way it does that
is in two steps.

660
00:42:48,810 --> 00:42:53,610
The first step is for your
model to which API there

661
00:42:53,610 --> 00:42:58,030
is out there, at the end
of which your LLM says,

662
00:42:58,030 --> 00:43:00,970
OK, I want to use
this API and I want

663
00:43:00,970 --> 00:43:04,890
to use it with these arguments.

664
00:43:04,890 --> 00:43:06,590
And then you have an
intermediary step,

665
00:43:06,590 --> 00:43:10,690
which is you just run your
API with these arguments.

666
00:43:10,690 --> 00:43:14,170
And then the second
step is you feed

667
00:43:14,170 --> 00:43:16,890
the results of
this operation back

668
00:43:16,890 --> 00:43:22,370
to the LLM, which then
produces a final answer.

669
00:43:22,370 --> 00:43:23,910
So that's how tool
calling works.

670
00:43:23,910 --> 00:43:29,570
So if you say to your
LLM, you can use this API,

671
00:43:29,570 --> 00:43:33,610
this is how your LLM
would leverage that.

672
00:43:33,610 --> 00:43:38,530
And then we saw that modern
day agentic workflows

673
00:43:38,530 --> 00:43:45,130
we're leveraging both RAG and
tool calling as key methods

674
00:43:45,130 --> 00:43:49,330
to perform actions.

675
00:43:49,330 --> 00:43:52,350
And we saw an
example, data example,

676
00:43:52,350 --> 00:43:54,810
which was such that
you had some inputs.

677
00:43:54,810 --> 00:44:00,570
And then your LLM had a
series of different calls

678
00:44:00,570 --> 00:44:02,270
in order to perform some action.

679
00:44:02,270 --> 00:44:05,470
And then at the end of
it, it retrieves-- sorry,

680
00:44:05,470 --> 00:44:06,790
it returns an answer.

681
00:44:09,970 --> 00:44:10,570
Cool.

682
00:44:10,570 --> 00:44:15,050
And then last
lecture, we saw how

683
00:44:15,050 --> 00:44:20,010
we could evaluate LLMs,
which is a much tougher thing

684
00:44:20,010 --> 00:44:24,930
to do now that LLMs can do
a bunch of different things.

685
00:44:24,930 --> 00:44:30,810
So we first saw that there
was some rule based metrics

686
00:44:30,810 --> 00:44:35,850
that people were using before
LLMs came into play, metrics

687
00:44:35,850 --> 00:44:42,940
that you may have heard like
BLEU, ROUGE, METEOR, and so on.

688
00:44:42,940 --> 00:44:46,620
But the main limitation
was that they were not

689
00:44:46,620 --> 00:44:52,980
considering how language could
differ, but still be correct.

690
00:44:52,980 --> 00:44:59,220
And so this key idea that we
saw was why not leverage LLMs

691
00:44:59,220 --> 00:45:01,340
to evaluate outputs.

692
00:45:01,340 --> 00:45:05,060
And so there is
this key idea of LLM

693
00:45:05,060 --> 00:45:11,340
as a judge where you receive
as input the prompts.

694
00:45:11,340 --> 00:45:14,580
The model response
along with the criteria

695
00:45:14,580 --> 00:45:19,220
that you want the response
to be evaluated on.

696
00:45:19,220 --> 00:45:23,860
And then you want your
LLMs to output two things.

697
00:45:23,860 --> 00:45:31,020
The first one is a rationale
for why a given score is outputs

698
00:45:31,020 --> 00:45:34,820
along with that score.

699
00:45:34,820 --> 00:45:38,420
So nowadays, LLM as the
judges are typically

700
00:45:38,420 --> 00:45:42,860
outputting a binary
response, either pass

701
00:45:42,860 --> 00:45:46,220
or fail, true or false,
just because it's easier.

702
00:45:46,220 --> 00:45:49,620
And we're also
having the rationale

703
00:45:49,620 --> 00:45:54,900
be output before the score,
because in practice it's

704
00:45:54,900 --> 00:45:59,460
something that also improves
the performance of the LLM

705
00:45:59,460 --> 00:46:00,460
as a judge.

706
00:46:00,460 --> 00:46:02,780
A little bit if you want,
like reasoning models

707
00:46:02,780 --> 00:46:04,900
do, by outputting
the reasoning chain

708
00:46:04,900 --> 00:46:06,680
before they output the answer.

709
00:46:09,380 --> 00:46:12,620
But then we also saw that
there were some biases that

710
00:46:12,620 --> 00:46:13,800
came with this approach.

711
00:46:13,800 --> 00:46:19,260
We saw a position bias,
which is the way you present

712
00:46:19,260 --> 00:46:21,440
the LLMs to compare matters.

713
00:46:21,440 --> 00:46:23,760
So if you present
something first,

714
00:46:23,760 --> 00:46:27,860
then maybe the LLM will
just prioritize that first.

715
00:46:27,860 --> 00:46:29,160
So there's position bias.

716
00:46:29,160 --> 00:46:33,300
There was verbosity bias, which
is your LLM just preferring

717
00:46:33,300 --> 00:46:35,660
longer outputs.

718
00:46:35,660 --> 00:46:38,460
And self-enhancement bias
was another one where

719
00:46:38,460 --> 00:46:42,460
it prefers its own outputs.

720
00:46:42,460 --> 00:46:46,300
And then we also saw
a number of benchmarks

721
00:46:46,300 --> 00:46:48,940
that people use
nowadays in order

722
00:46:48,940 --> 00:46:52,140
to say how great their LLM is.

723
00:46:52,140 --> 00:46:55,700
So if you see the
releases that come out,

724
00:46:55,700 --> 00:46:57,940
there are typically
a bunch of metrics

725
00:46:57,940 --> 00:47:00,340
across a number of
different benchmarks

726
00:47:00,340 --> 00:47:01,720
that people know about.

727
00:47:01,720 --> 00:47:05,940
So that spans
knowledge, the ability

728
00:47:05,940 --> 00:47:09,340
to reason coding, which is
very important because a lot

729
00:47:09,340 --> 00:47:13,960
of applications are coding
related, and then safety.

730
00:47:13,960 --> 00:47:17,800
And then this is not
an extensive list.

731
00:47:17,800 --> 00:47:20,400
So there's actually
many more dimensions.

732
00:47:23,940 --> 00:47:26,780
So yeah, I think that's
where we stopped.

733
00:47:26,780 --> 00:47:30,020
And it was last lecture.

734
00:47:30,020 --> 00:47:37,390
And this is all you're
expected to know for the final.

735
00:47:37,390 --> 00:47:41,650
Everything after that is not
going to be part of the final.

736
