And this one is 5, 6, 7, 8.

753
00:48:39,930 --> 00:48:42,850
So I guess it's equal size.

754
00:48:45,990 --> 00:48:47,910
Cool?

755
00:48:47,910 --> 00:48:49,510
OK, great.

756
00:48:49,510 --> 00:48:52,630
So with that said,
we just finished

757
00:48:52,630 --> 00:48:57,150
recapping this entire
quarter worth of lectures.

758
00:48:57,150 --> 00:49:01,410
And now we're going to go to
the second item of today's menu,

759
00:49:01,410 --> 00:49:06,830
which is looking at
some trending topics.

760
00:49:06,830 --> 00:49:10,670
And so I'm going to
start with the first one.

761
00:49:10,670 --> 00:49:14,270
And I'm going to
introduce it as follows.

762
00:49:14,270 --> 00:49:18,350
So if you remember, we
saw that the transformer

763
00:49:18,350 --> 00:49:21,270
was a concept and
an architecture that

764
00:49:21,270 --> 00:49:26,630
was first introduced in the
context of machine translation.

765
00:49:26,630 --> 00:49:28,880
So it performed great.

766
00:49:28,880 --> 00:49:31,620
People said, OK, it performs
great on machine translation,

767
00:49:31,620 --> 00:49:35,720
why not try it on
other text tasks.

768
00:49:35,720 --> 00:49:36,560
So they tried it.

769
00:49:36,560 --> 00:49:38,680
Performed great.

770
00:49:38,680 --> 00:49:41,800
But now the question
is, can you not use it

771
00:49:41,800 --> 00:49:45,920
for things other than texts.

772
00:49:45,920 --> 00:49:48,520
It's a natural question.

773
00:49:48,520 --> 00:49:51,840
So in order to
answer that question,

774
00:49:51,840 --> 00:49:54,640
I just want us to
remind ourselves

775
00:49:54,640 --> 00:50:00,000
that this architecture is
relying on this concept of self

776
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:01,720
attention.

777
00:50:01,720 --> 00:50:07,280
And this is what is making
the transformer work so well.

778
00:50:07,280 --> 00:50:13,360
So if we just recap
what self-attention is--

779
00:50:13,360 --> 00:50:18,120
this illustration kind of
does the job quite well--

780
00:50:18,120 --> 00:50:20,840
you have a query,
and then you have

781
00:50:20,840 --> 00:50:23,880
a bunch of other elements,
which are represented

782
00:50:23,880 --> 00:50:26,440
by your keys and your values.

783
00:50:26,440 --> 00:50:30,600
And you want to know which
other elements are actually

784
00:50:30,600 --> 00:50:37,720
relevant in order to compute
the embedding for that query.

785
00:50:37,720 --> 00:50:43,560
So right now, we have only
used tokens, text tokens.

786
00:50:43,560 --> 00:50:50,160
But text tokens, they're
actually vectors.

787
00:50:50,160 --> 00:50:55,120
So if you take those
vectors, and you actually

788
00:50:55,120 --> 00:50:58,600
represent something
else than text--

789
00:50:58,600 --> 00:51:02,080
like for instance,
parts of an image--

790
00:51:02,080 --> 00:51:07,440
the question is,
would the transformer

791
00:51:07,440 --> 00:51:11,340
based on that kind of
input also perform well.

792
00:51:14,440 --> 00:51:18,760
And so here the key
question that I want to ask

793
00:51:18,760 --> 00:51:23,360
is, how can we adapt
our transformer

794
00:51:23,360 --> 00:51:26,940
to work on non-text input.

795
00:51:26,940 --> 00:51:29,880
And for instance, here we can
think of image understanding

796
00:51:29,880 --> 00:51:30,380
input.

797
00:51:30,380 --> 00:51:32,520
So you have some image.

798
00:51:32,520 --> 00:51:35,960
And so it's a traditional
computer vision

799
00:51:35,960 --> 00:51:41,320
task where you want to in which
class this image belongs to.

800
00:51:41,320 --> 00:51:45,760
So you want to know if
having some transformer based

801
00:51:45,760 --> 00:51:49,360
architecture would work
well in that situation.

802
00:51:49,360 --> 00:51:53,600
Well, the answer to
that is, well, first,

803
00:51:53,600 --> 00:51:56,640
in order to adapt
it to this task,

804
00:51:56,640 --> 00:52:03,020
you would take the encoder
parts of the transformer

805
00:52:03,020 --> 00:52:07,480
because in order to understand
what is in an image,

806
00:52:07,480 --> 00:52:11,240
you need to classify
that image in some sense.

807
00:52:11,240 --> 00:52:14,480
So if you remember, if
there is a one model--

808
00:52:14,480 --> 00:52:18,760
and what we saw that was working
very well for classification

809
00:52:18,760 --> 00:52:22,950
was BERT, because
BERT is encoder only.

810
00:52:22,950 --> 00:52:26,410
It computes
meaningful embeddings

811
00:52:26,410 --> 00:52:30,130
that can then be used
for projection purposes

812
00:52:30,130 --> 00:52:33,610
or for classification purposes.

813
00:52:33,610 --> 00:52:37,890
So it's a very natural choice
that here we would have.

814
00:52:37,890 --> 00:52:41,650
So here, we would just keep the
encoder part of the transformer

815
00:52:41,650 --> 00:52:47,330
and then have the self-attention
mechanism come into play

816
00:52:47,330 --> 00:52:52,090
and compute meaningful
embeddings that we could then

817
00:52:52,090 --> 00:52:55,890
project for our relevant task.

818
00:52:55,890 --> 00:53:02,290
And this is exactly what a group
of researchers did back in 2020.

819
00:53:02,290 --> 00:53:07,170
So have you heard of
VIT, vision transformer.

820
00:53:07,170 --> 00:53:09,090
Yeah, no, yeah?

821
00:53:09,090 --> 00:53:13,410
So what I described here
is exactly what they did.

822
00:53:13,410 --> 00:53:16,210
So they took an image.

823
00:53:16,210 --> 00:53:21,330
They divided that
image into patches.

824
00:53:21,330 --> 00:53:26,930
Those patches were
represented by some vectors.

825
00:53:26,930 --> 00:53:30,410
And of course, you have some
kind of position information

826
00:53:30,410 --> 00:53:35,970
that allows you to know where
your patches in the image.

827
00:53:35,970 --> 00:53:38,870
And then you just put it
through the transformer encoder.

828
00:53:38,870 --> 00:53:41,650
So the encoder part
of the transformer.

829
00:53:41,650 --> 00:53:45,250
And you compute the
representation corresponding

830
00:53:45,250 --> 00:53:49,330
to the CLS class,
very similar to BERT.

831
00:53:49,330 --> 00:53:52,770
And you would just project
that representation

832
00:53:52,770 --> 00:53:57,410
over some classes of interest.

833
00:53:57,410 --> 00:54:04,530
And then you would perform your,
I guess, computation like this.

834
00:54:04,530 --> 00:54:10,050
So what that paper found
was that if you train such

835
00:54:10,050 --> 00:54:15,450
a model on a lot of image
data, a lot of image data,

836
00:54:15,450 --> 00:54:19,770
you then outperform these is
traditional convolutional neural

837
00:54:19,770 --> 00:54:23,250
network kind of methods.

838
00:54:23,250 --> 00:54:28,510
And it was kind of
remarkable because.

839
00:54:28,510 --> 00:54:30,370
So why is it remarkable.

840
00:54:30,370 --> 00:54:33,370
Because in the vision case.

841
00:54:33,370 --> 00:54:37,410
So there is this concept
of inductive bias

842
00:54:37,410 --> 00:54:43,130
where you want to gear
your model towards looking

843
00:54:43,130 --> 00:54:48,930
at certain things in order
to deduce the results.

844
00:54:48,930 --> 00:54:54,210
So convolutional neural
networks are a kind of model

845
00:54:54,210 --> 00:54:57,250
that are designed
in a way for you

846
00:54:57,250 --> 00:55:02,230
to look at the image
in some sliding way.

847
00:55:02,230 --> 00:55:03,730
You look at your
image a little bit

848
00:55:03,730 --> 00:55:08,570
like you would look at it
in practice as a human.

849
00:55:08,570 --> 00:55:13,330
And people had hypothesized
that such a bias, such

850
00:55:13,330 --> 00:55:16,900
an inductive bias would actually
make sense for something

851
00:55:16,900 --> 00:55:19,100
like a vision task.

852
00:55:19,100 --> 00:55:22,820
So you contrast that with
the vision transformer, which

853
00:55:22,820 --> 00:55:27,820
is actually letting all parts
of the image attend to one

854
00:55:27,820 --> 00:55:33,460
another, which has, on the other
side, very low inductive bias.

855
00:55:33,460 --> 00:55:40,740
So what this paper showed was if
you give your model enough data,

856
00:55:40,740 --> 00:55:45,660
then it will actually learn
how to classify, I guess,

857
00:55:45,660 --> 00:55:47,280
your images in these classes.

858
00:55:47,280 --> 00:55:51,420
So this was kind of
a remarkable result.

859
00:55:51,420 --> 00:55:53,380
So I think this was
pretty remarkable

860
00:55:53,380 --> 00:55:57,140
and a nice extension
of everything we saw.

861
00:55:57,140 --> 00:56:01,140
So with that in mind,
I want us to just go

862
00:56:01,140 --> 00:56:06,980
through an end to end example of
how you would process an image

863
00:56:06,980 --> 00:56:12,180
and go through that VIT,
so vision transformer,

864
00:56:12,180 --> 00:56:15,520
in order to make
your prediction.

865
00:56:15,520 --> 00:56:18,580
So here, you would take
your favorite image

866
00:56:18,580 --> 00:56:21,780
that you would just
split into patches.

867
00:56:21,780 --> 00:56:27,260
So here, you can think of you
predefining some fixed size

868
00:56:27,260 --> 00:56:29,420
patches.

869
00:56:29,420 --> 00:56:31,680
So here, I would say
3 by 3, let's say.

870
00:56:31,680 --> 00:56:37,260
And then each patch has
some fixed number of pixels.

871
00:56:37,260 --> 00:56:40,700
And then what you do
is for each patch,

872
00:56:40,700 --> 00:56:45,540
you try to have some
vector representation.

873
00:56:45,540 --> 00:56:49,300
So you can think
of each patch as--

874
00:56:49,300 --> 00:56:50,680
so what is the patch.

875
00:56:50,680 --> 00:56:53,220
So it's composed of pixels.

876
00:56:53,220 --> 00:56:56,700
So if each pixel has
three values which

877
00:56:56,700 --> 00:56:59,660
correspond to red,
green, and blue,

878
00:56:59,660 --> 00:57:05,580
then you can find a way to
project those on some lower

879
00:57:05,580 --> 00:57:08,900
dimensional flattened space.

880
00:57:08,900 --> 00:57:11,780
And you can learn how
you would project that

881
00:57:11,780 --> 00:57:14,870
through some kind
of linear layer.

882
00:57:14,870 --> 00:57:22,950
So long story short, you just
find a way to associate a vector

883
00:57:22,950 --> 00:57:29,470
to each of these patches,
which you then represent

884
00:57:29,470 --> 00:57:31,750
every single one of your input.

885
00:57:31,750 --> 00:57:35,230
And then you have, of course,
a special embedding for the CLS

886
00:57:35,230 --> 00:57:38,830
token, which you can
also learn, and you

887
00:57:38,830 --> 00:57:42,470
add the position embedding.

888
00:57:42,470 --> 00:57:45,470
So you do the same for
all of your inputs.

889
00:57:45,470 --> 00:57:48,990
And then very similar
to BERT, Just put that

890
00:57:48,990 --> 00:57:50,430
through your encoder.

891
00:57:50,430 --> 00:57:54,110
Let everyone interact
with everyone.

892
00:57:54,110 --> 00:57:57,230
And then at the end of the
day, what you care about

893
00:57:57,230 --> 00:58:01,870
is a representation of the
input that is meaningful.

894
00:58:01,870 --> 00:58:05,430
So typically, people take
the encoder embedding

895
00:58:05,430 --> 00:58:07,510
of the CLS token.

896
00:58:07,510 --> 00:58:09,790
So the reason why
they take that is one,

897
00:58:09,790 --> 00:58:11,290
because it's a convention.

898
00:58:11,290 --> 00:58:15,350
But the second one
is this CLS token.

899
00:58:15,350 --> 00:58:19,790
So the encoded
embedding is actually

900
00:58:19,790 --> 00:58:24,510
an embedding that has
interacted with all other tokens

901
00:58:24,510 --> 00:58:27,510
through this
self-attention mechanism.

902
00:58:27,510 --> 00:58:29,950
So it has seen everything.

903
00:58:29,950 --> 00:58:35,390
And then you would project
that CLS token encoded

904
00:58:35,390 --> 00:58:38,870
embedding onto some
class through a feed

905
00:58:38,870 --> 00:58:45,110
forward neural network in order
to predict your final class.

906
00:58:45,110 --> 00:58:47,770
So in this case, we know it's
a picture of a Teddy bear.

907
00:58:47,770 --> 00:58:50,550
So here, we would want
the model to classify

908
00:58:50,550 --> 00:58:51,690
this as a Teddy bear.

909
00:58:54,390 --> 00:58:56,230
So far so good?

910
00:58:56,230 --> 00:58:57,250
Does that make sense?

911
00:59:00,710 --> 00:59:01,730
Cool.

912
00:59:01,730 --> 00:59:08,550
So now we know how to process
image input right now.

913
00:59:08,550 --> 00:59:17,550
So another question is, how
would you have your LLM answer

914
00:59:17,550 --> 00:59:20,368
questions about your image,
which is something that you

915
00:59:20,368 --> 00:59:21,410
can do actually nowadays.

916
00:59:21,410 --> 00:59:25,150
If you open ChatGPT,
you can input an image

917
00:59:25,150 --> 00:59:28,430
and ask it questions.

918
00:59:28,430 --> 00:59:32,770
So you would have
two kinds of inputs.

919
00:59:32,770 --> 00:59:38,030
So you would have an image which
we can find a way to represent,

920
00:59:38,030 --> 00:59:41,750
and then the text, which
you now know very well how

921
00:59:41,750 --> 00:59:44,910
to represent with tokens.

922
00:59:44,910 --> 00:59:48,910
So the way you would
allow the model

923
00:59:48,910 --> 00:59:54,070
or let the model
process all of this

924
00:59:54,070 --> 00:59:56,850
is typically as follows-- so
there are a couple of methods.

925
00:59:56,850 --> 01:00:00,470
The first one is the most
common one, which is you just

926
01:00:00,470 --> 01:00:03,190
feed everything as input.

927
01:00:03,190 --> 01:00:08,600
So the image token as input,
the text tokens as inputs.

928
01:00:08,600 --> 01:00:12,550
And you have some representation
to have the model just

929
01:00:12,550 --> 01:00:16,000
know that these are image
tokens and this is text token.

930
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:20,480
And then you let it
generate an answer

931
01:00:20,480 --> 01:00:24,040
in a decoder only fashion,
autoregressive fashion

932
01:00:24,040 --> 01:00:27,400
exactly like you would do it.

933
01:00:27,400 --> 01:00:30,480
The first method and
a lot of such models

934
01:00:30,480 --> 01:00:33,000
are designed that way.

935
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:38,300
So there is, for instance,
a very popular open weight,

936
01:00:38,300 --> 01:00:42,100
I believe vision
language model, VLM--

937
01:00:42,100 --> 01:00:46,240
that's what they are called
a model called LAVA--

938
01:00:46,240 --> 01:00:47,420
And this is how they do it.

939
01:00:47,420 --> 01:00:51,160
So they have some encoder
on the image parts

940
01:00:51,160 --> 01:00:55,240
that produces some
tokens that are then

941
01:00:55,240 --> 01:01:00,520
concatenated with text tokens
that are inputs into the LLM.

942
01:01:00,520 --> 01:01:03,400
So that's one method.

943
01:01:03,400 --> 01:01:06,080
The second method,
which is less common,

944
01:01:06,080 --> 01:01:15,400
is to have the images be inputs
at the cross-attention layer.

945
01:01:15,400 --> 01:01:19,920
So here, what you would do
is you have your text inputs.

946
01:01:19,920 --> 01:01:23,580
And then your image inputs,
you don't put it in the inputs.

947
01:01:23,580 --> 01:01:27,720
You actually let it interact
with the text tokens

948
01:01:27,720 --> 01:01:31,760
within the
cross-attention layer.

949
01:01:31,760 --> 01:01:35,080
And this is something
that, for instance, Llama 3

950
01:01:35,080 --> 01:01:38,440
had represented in their paper.

951
01:01:38,440 --> 01:01:40,500
This technique is
typically less common.

952
01:01:40,500 --> 01:01:45,040
The first one is more common.

953
01:01:45,040 --> 01:01:51,520
So I guess what I want
to say is CME 295 focused

954
01:01:51,520 --> 01:01:56,320
on the transformer specifically
in the case of text

955
01:01:56,320 --> 01:01:58,080
to text problems.

956
01:01:58,080 --> 01:02:02,360
So text generation
is all this class.

957
01:02:02,360 --> 01:02:06,040
But we also have the
transformer that was

958
01:02:06,040 --> 01:02:08,820
used for non-text applications.

959
01:02:08,820 --> 01:02:11,180
So here, we saw
image understanding.

960
01:02:11,180 --> 01:02:14,160
So vision
understanding with VIT.

961
01:02:14,160 --> 01:02:18,460
And then we will not have
the time to see this now.

962
01:02:18,460 --> 01:02:22,560
But also for image
generation tasks,

963
01:02:22,560 --> 01:02:25,960
we can also have parts
of the transformer

964
01:02:25,960 --> 01:02:29,320
be used in that architecture.

965
01:02:29,320 --> 01:02:33,600
And so you may hear about
diffusion transformer

966
01:02:33,600 --> 01:02:36,920
or multimodal
diffusion transformer

967
01:02:36,920 --> 01:02:41,000
that actually rely on the
self-attention mechanism.

968
01:02:41,000 --> 01:02:45,040
And this is actually
not an exhaustive list.

969
01:02:45,040 --> 01:02:47,040
This is also something
that has been

970
01:02:47,040 --> 01:02:54,080
used in other domains like
recommendation speech and so on.

971
01:02:54,080 --> 01:02:56,720
So I guess what I
want you to remember

972
01:02:56,720 --> 01:03:04,650
from this is that transformers
was an architecture that

973
01:03:04,650 --> 01:03:08,970
performed very well for
machine translation tasks.

974
01:03:08,970 --> 01:03:13,090
But then it proved
to perform very well

975
01:03:13,090 --> 01:03:16,170
for other text related tasks.

976
01:03:16,170 --> 01:03:18,170
And it was then
reused in a bunch

977
01:03:18,170 --> 01:03:22,610
of other domains, which also
proved to be quite successful.

978
01:03:22,610 --> 01:03:24,890
So I would just encourage
you, after this class,

979
01:03:24,890 --> 01:03:30,610
to also keep an open mind for
non-text related transformer

980
01:03:30,610 --> 01:03:32,210
applications.

981
01:03:32,210 --> 01:03:34,450
And the ones that
I mentioned here

982
01:03:34,450 --> 01:03:38,410
are maybe just a few first few
pointers into the kind of papers

983
01:03:38,410 --> 01:03:41,770
that you can look at.

984
01:03:41,770 --> 01:03:42,670
Cool.

985
01:03:42,670 --> 01:03:45,250
So here, we said
that transformer

986
01:03:45,250 --> 01:03:50,570
was something that came from the
text world that's also useful

987
01:03:50,570 --> 01:03:53,370
and used in other worlds.

988
01:03:53,370 --> 01:03:56,930
Now I want to tell you
about something else that

989
01:03:56,930 --> 01:04:04,050
was, I guess, used and useful
in the non-text worlds that may

990
01:04:04,050 --> 01:04:06,970
be useful in the text world.

991
01:04:06,970 --> 01:04:11,770
And I want to tell you
about diffusion-based LLMs.

992
01:04:11,770 --> 01:04:15,530
So who has heard
the term diffusion?

993
01:04:15,530 --> 01:04:18,250
Who knows about diffusion?

994
01:04:18,250 --> 01:04:19,930
Yeah.

995
01:04:19,930 --> 01:04:20,430
Cool.

996
01:04:20,430 --> 01:04:23,070
So we will see how we
can apply that to LLMs.

997
01:04:23,070 --> 01:04:25,310
So this is a very trendy topic.

998
01:04:25,310 --> 01:04:29,070
I believe the first paper
started in the early 2020s,

999
01:04:29,070 --> 01:04:34,650
but I guess it's only now that
people are starting to have this

1000
01:04:34,650 --> 01:04:37,850
really work.

1001
01:04:37,850 --> 01:04:40,530
I just want to start with
the motivation, which

1002
01:04:40,530 --> 01:04:46,370
is that up until now, we have
taken for granted the fact

1003
01:04:46,370 --> 01:04:50,530
that our LLM is an
autoregressive LLM.

1004
01:04:50,530 --> 01:04:54,290
And by autoregressive,
what do I mean by that?

1005
01:04:54,290 --> 01:04:58,100
So it takes some input.

1006
01:04:58,100 --> 01:05:03,580
And what the LLM tries to do
is to predict the next token.

1007
01:05:03,580 --> 01:05:08,860
So given everything so far,
we predict the next token.

1008
01:05:08,860 --> 01:05:12,260
We do that, and then
we take that token

1009
01:05:12,260 --> 01:05:14,420
that we just predicted,
along with everything

1010
01:05:14,420 --> 01:05:17,620
that we have predicted so far.

1011
01:05:17,620 --> 01:05:22,580
And then we, again,
predict the next token.

1012
01:05:22,580 --> 01:05:26,380
We predict it and we
go again and again,

1013
01:05:26,380 --> 01:05:29,900
up until finishing the sequence
with that end of sequence

1014
01:05:29,900 --> 01:05:33,620
token, which makes
the generation stop.

1015
01:05:33,620 --> 01:05:37,340
So this is a true
autoregressive generation,

1016
01:05:37,340 --> 01:05:40,700
as in we take the
input so far in order

1017
01:05:40,700 --> 01:05:43,500
to predict the next token.

1018
01:05:43,500 --> 01:05:47,000
And then we repeat this
process until the end.

1019
01:05:49,820 --> 01:05:53,540
So it's something
that people now

1020
01:05:53,540 --> 01:05:58,540
try to give it a name, which
is like autoregressive model

1021
01:05:58,540 --> 01:05:59,400
kind of model.

1022
01:05:59,400 --> 01:06:06,620
So ARM, if you see this
notation, that's what it means.

1023
01:06:06,620 --> 01:06:08,820
The problem with
that kind of paradigm

1024
01:06:08,820 --> 01:06:13,580
is that inference time
generation is actually

1025
01:06:13,580 --> 01:06:16,700
not something you
can parallelize,

1026
01:06:16,700 --> 01:06:20,540
because you always need
what's before in order

1027
01:06:20,540 --> 01:06:21,800
to predict the next one.

1028
01:06:24,420 --> 01:06:27,820
But I just want to say that
inference time generation is not

1029
01:06:27,820 --> 01:06:34,500
parallelizable, but
training is parallelizable.

1030
01:06:34,500 --> 01:06:37,180
So if you remember, the
way we do training is we

1031
01:06:37,180 --> 01:06:44,460
input all the tokens that
we want our model to predict

1032
01:06:44,460 --> 01:06:51,960
and then we let the model
generate tokens out of this.

1033
01:06:51,960 --> 01:06:54,020
So basically in a
decoder only setting

1034
01:06:54,020 --> 01:06:58,900
you have this causal mask
which lets your model not

1035
01:06:58,900 --> 01:07:04,100
cheat if you want and
not use the future ones.

1036
01:07:04,100 --> 01:07:08,420
So I just want to say that when
I say that this paradigm is not

1037
01:07:08,420 --> 01:07:10,660
parallelizable, I just want
to emphasize on the fact

1038
01:07:10,660 --> 01:07:12,860
that it's an inference
time that I'm saying.

1039
01:07:12,860 --> 01:07:15,720
Training time, you can actually
parallelize that quite well.

1040
01:07:18,340 --> 01:07:21,660
So as I mentioned,
that's one of the reasons

1041
01:07:21,660 --> 01:07:26,060
why people have tried to
look at other paradigms.

1042
01:07:26,060 --> 01:07:29,580
And in particular, so if
you know about diffusion,

1043
01:07:29,580 --> 01:07:33,740
you know that it works very
well for the vision domain.

1044
01:07:33,740 --> 01:07:38,020
And so people have tried
adapting this paradigm

1045
01:07:38,020 --> 01:07:41,220
for the text generation case.

1046
01:07:41,220 --> 01:07:43,420
And so this is a
bunch of screenshots

1047
01:07:43,420 --> 01:07:47,120
we took from an announcement
that happened this year.

1048
01:07:47,120 --> 01:07:49,380
So for instance,
earlier this year,

1049
01:07:49,380 --> 01:07:53,590
there was an experimental text
diffusion model from Google

1050
01:07:53,590 --> 01:07:57,870
that they presented during
the I/O event, which

1051
01:07:57,870 --> 01:08:00,910
was very impressive because
it led to a lot of speed ups.

1052
01:08:00,910 --> 01:08:04,690
And then we have some
different startups.

1053
01:08:04,690 --> 01:08:07,310
So Inception is one
of them that made

1054
01:08:07,310 --> 01:08:10,470
headlines I believe a couple
of weeks ago, or last week.

1055
01:08:10,470 --> 01:08:13,150
No, sorry, a month ago.

1056
01:08:13,150 --> 01:08:15,990
That also are
pursuing this route.

1057
01:08:15,990 --> 01:08:19,550
So all of that to say
that this direction is

1058
01:08:19,550 --> 01:08:23,830
a very trendy and hot
direction that potentially

1059
01:08:23,830 --> 01:08:27,029
has a lot of promise.

1060
01:08:27,029 --> 01:08:34,069
But the key issue with this
is that text is discrete,

1061
01:08:34,069 --> 01:08:37,990
whereas images are continuous.

1062
01:08:37,990 --> 01:08:42,149
And we're going to see why that
distinction that I just made

1063
01:08:42,149 --> 01:08:43,910
matters.

1064
01:08:43,910 --> 01:08:46,189
So I'm going to try
to explain to you what

1065
01:08:46,189 --> 01:08:49,189
diffusion is in two minutes.

1066
01:08:49,189 --> 01:08:54,870
So in the image world,
in order to generate

1067
01:08:54,870 --> 01:09:02,189
an image, what people typically
do is they start from noise,

1068
01:09:02,189 --> 01:09:06,470
and then they try to
generate some image.

1069
01:09:06,470 --> 01:09:09,109
Now you may wonder,
OK, why noise.

1070
01:09:09,109 --> 01:09:15,170
Well, you cannot do something
autoregressive because I guess,

1071
01:09:15,170 --> 01:09:17,990
if you were to say, OK,
let's predict the pixels one

1072
01:09:17,990 --> 01:09:21,830
at a time, it's just not
tractable because there are many

1073
01:09:21,830 --> 01:09:23,210
pixels in an image.

1074
01:09:23,210 --> 01:09:26,910
And this is typically not how
you would produce an image.

1075
01:09:26,910 --> 01:09:32,189
But some other reasons are
that noise is just something

1076
01:09:32,189 --> 01:09:35,630
that you can model very
well with some very

1077
01:09:35,630 --> 01:09:36,810
popular distributions.

1078
01:09:36,810 --> 01:09:39,910
So Gaussian distribution,
if you about it,

1079
01:09:39,910 --> 01:09:43,029
it has very nice properties.

1080
01:09:43,029 --> 01:09:44,950
Also, noise is very
easy to sample.

1081
01:09:44,950 --> 01:09:48,279
So it's very easy
to start with that.

1082
01:09:48,279 --> 01:09:52,800
Noise is also a way for you
to introduce randomness,

1083
01:09:52,800 --> 01:09:55,000
because you don't necessarily
want to always produce

1084
01:09:55,000 --> 01:09:55,940
the same image.

1085
01:09:55,940 --> 01:10:02,760
You want to have, I guess,
choice of generating images

1086
01:10:02,760 --> 01:10:05,920
that are slightly
different from one another.

1087
01:10:05,920 --> 01:10:09,600
And just mathematically,
it works quite well.

1088
01:10:09,600 --> 01:10:14,360
And speaking of
that, the goal is

1089
01:10:14,360 --> 01:10:18,320
to learn some
transformation that

1090
01:10:18,320 --> 01:10:24,320
would allow you to go from
noise to the target image

1091
01:10:24,320 --> 01:10:26,680
distribution.

1092
01:10:26,680 --> 01:10:30,800
So all of what I said here
is just reasons for me

1093
01:10:30,800 --> 01:10:33,960
to tell you noise
is actually a choice

1094
01:10:33,960 --> 01:10:37,080
that is quite
natural to start with

1095
01:10:37,080 --> 01:10:39,920
in order to generate an image.

1096
01:10:39,920 --> 01:10:47,160
And to give you an analogy,
let's suppose you're a sculptor.

1097
01:10:47,160 --> 01:10:50,000
So the person who
does sculptures.

1098
01:10:50,000 --> 01:10:52,100
So if you want to
do a sculpture,

1099
01:10:52,100 --> 01:10:57,880
you typically start
with some rock.

1100
01:10:57,880 --> 01:11:01,300
But then rocks are
different from one another.

1101
01:11:01,300 --> 01:11:05,440
They always have things
that are unique to them.

1102
01:11:05,440 --> 01:11:13,080
And still, you would focus
on what to remove in order

1103
01:11:13,080 --> 01:11:16,640
to obtain the end sculpture.

1104
01:11:16,640 --> 01:11:20,400
So you can think of the
rock as being your noise,

1105
01:11:20,400 --> 01:11:26,200
and your end result as being
your target data distribution.

1106
01:11:26,200 --> 01:11:29,160
So I just want to have
this quote by Michelangelo.

1107
01:11:29,160 --> 01:11:31,600
So the sculpture is already
complete within the marble

1108
01:11:31,600 --> 01:11:32,560
block.

1109
01:11:32,560 --> 01:11:35,260
Before I start my work,
it is already there.

1110
01:11:35,260 --> 01:11:38,560
I just have to chisel away
the superfluous material.

1111
01:11:38,560 --> 01:11:40,480
The reason why I'm
reading that is you

1112
01:11:40,480 --> 01:11:45,700
can have a nice analogy
between what Michelangelo said

1113
01:11:45,700 --> 01:11:54,640
and the process of de-noising
the noise to get an image.

1114
01:11:54,640 --> 01:11:58,300
So this is all just motivating
how image generation is done.

1115
01:11:58,300 --> 01:12:03,600
So you start from noise, and
you want to generate an image.

1116
01:12:03,600 --> 01:12:05,880
So the way you do
that for diffusion

1117
01:12:05,880 --> 01:12:09,640
is to learn some
transformation that would allow

1118
01:12:09,640 --> 01:12:13,580
you to go from noise to image.

1119
01:12:16,160 --> 01:12:17,518
So you have two steps.

1120
01:12:17,518 --> 01:12:19,060
I mean, you have
more than two steps,

1121
01:12:19,060 --> 01:12:21,840
but we have these two main
steps for diffusion models

1122
01:12:21,840 --> 01:12:28,360
where you first want to
start from clean images.

1123
01:12:28,360 --> 01:12:33,520
And you add noise
gradually until you

1124
01:12:33,520 --> 01:12:37,560
obtain some very noisy image.

1125
01:12:37,560 --> 01:12:43,370
And then from that, what
diffusion models try to do

1126
01:12:43,370 --> 01:12:48,210
is to predict the noise
to remove in order

1127
01:12:48,210 --> 01:12:51,050
to obtain the image.

1128
01:12:51,050 --> 01:12:55,890
So it's a little bit like
you're the sculpture person.

1129
01:12:55,890 --> 01:12:57,070
And you have your rock.

1130
01:12:57,070 --> 01:12:59,730
You just want to learn
what pieces of rock

1131
01:12:59,730 --> 01:13:05,170
you need to remove in order to
obtain your final piece of art.

1132
01:13:05,170 --> 01:13:07,690
So this is what diffusion is.

1133
01:13:07,690 --> 01:13:12,310
So it works pretty well
because noise, as I mentioned,

1134
01:13:12,310 --> 01:13:15,450
is typically something
that people draw

1135
01:13:15,450 --> 01:13:18,250
from a Gaussian distribution.

1136
01:13:18,250 --> 01:13:21,010
Gaussian distributions
are mathematically

1137
01:13:21,010 --> 01:13:25,010
very well defined, have
a lot of nice properties.

1138
01:13:25,010 --> 01:13:28,610
So that's why they work so well.

1139
01:13:28,610 --> 01:13:30,570
But now the question
is, how would you

1140
01:13:30,570 --> 01:13:33,430
adapt this to the text world.

1141
01:13:33,430 --> 01:13:35,530
Because in the text
world, as you know,

1142
01:13:35,530 --> 01:13:38,730
we're talking about tokens.

1143
01:13:38,730 --> 01:13:41,130
Tokens are discrete.

1144
01:13:41,130 --> 01:13:44,370
So there's not this
concept adding noise.

1145
01:13:44,370 --> 01:13:47,290
You cannot have that.

1146
01:13:47,290 --> 01:13:52,290
So what people have
tried to do was

1147
01:13:52,290 --> 01:13:56,370
to find a text equivalent
that would make sense.

1148
01:13:56,370 --> 01:14:00,130
And this is what
the current research

1149
01:14:00,130 --> 01:14:05,650
points to which is
that noise is to images

1150
01:14:05,650 --> 01:14:08,990
what the mask token is to text.

1151
01:14:11,650 --> 01:14:16,290
So mask is just a way
for us to just not

1152
01:14:16,290 --> 01:14:21,330
have the information coming
from one part of the sequence.

1153
01:14:21,330 --> 01:14:25,370
And I just want to go through
the revised 2-step process that

1154
01:14:25,370 --> 01:14:28,050
we saw here for text.

1155
01:14:28,050 --> 01:14:32,130
So here, for the
forward process,

1156
01:14:32,130 --> 01:14:35,410
instead of noising
your input, you

1157
01:14:35,410 --> 01:14:41,270
would just have more and more
inputs that would be masked.

1158
01:14:44,250 --> 01:14:45,750
So that's the full process.

1159
01:14:45,750 --> 01:14:48,650
And at the end, you would
just obtain a sequence

1160
01:14:48,650 --> 01:14:52,330
full of masked tokens.

1161
01:14:52,330 --> 01:14:59,490
So what you want to do is
to learn some model that

1162
01:14:59,490 --> 01:15:06,090
allows you to unmask these
masked tokens in a way that

1163
01:15:06,090 --> 01:15:10,610
reconstructs the
original sentence.

1164
01:15:10,610 --> 01:15:12,983
So there's some math
that goes into it.

1165
01:15:12,983 --> 01:15:14,650
Obviously, in a few
minutes, we will not

1166
01:15:14,650 --> 01:15:15,870
have time to go into that.

1167
01:15:15,870 --> 01:15:19,650
But I just want to emphasize
on the key idea, which

1168
01:15:19,650 --> 01:15:24,330
is you want to do
diffusion, but in a way that

1169
01:15:24,330 --> 01:15:27,050
makes sense for text inputs.

1170
01:15:27,050 --> 01:15:29,850
And the way it
would make sense is

1171
01:15:29,850 --> 01:15:33,650
to consider the noise
for images as being

1172
01:15:33,650 --> 01:15:38,120
mask tokens for text input.

1173
01:15:41,780 --> 01:15:42,380
Cool.

1174
01:15:42,380 --> 01:15:44,872
And so with that
in mind, you have

1175
01:15:44,872 --> 01:15:46,580
a bunch of models that
are being released

1176
01:15:46,580 --> 01:15:54,900
these days which are called
masked diffusion models, MDM.

1177
01:15:54,900 --> 01:15:58,580
So whenever you see MDM, now
you know what kind of model

1178
01:15:58,580 --> 01:16:00,300
we're talking about.

1179
01:16:00,300 --> 01:16:07,280
So notations are still
not very well defined.

1180
01:16:07,280 --> 01:16:09,740
So it may change in the future.

1181
01:16:09,740 --> 01:16:11,780
But one other term
you will see out there

1182
01:16:11,780 --> 01:16:18,140
is also DLLM,
diffusion based LLM.

1183
01:16:18,140 --> 01:16:20,560
And this is what it's doing.

1184
01:16:20,560 --> 01:16:26,660
So instead of predicting a token
in an autoregressive fashion one

1185
01:16:26,660 --> 01:16:31,140
at a time, what it does
is that at inference time,

1186
01:16:31,140 --> 01:16:37,220
it goes from a completely
masked input sequence.

1187
01:16:37,220 --> 01:16:41,820
And it tries to predict what
tokens were behind these mask

1188
01:16:41,820 --> 01:16:44,340
tokens.

1189
01:16:44,340 --> 01:16:47,340
So of course, in a
real life setting,

1190
01:16:47,340 --> 01:16:49,660
you would have
some prompts here.

1191
01:16:49,660 --> 01:16:51,020
You would have some prompts.

1192
01:16:51,020 --> 01:16:54,860
So of course, in order
to predict these answer,

1193
01:16:54,860 --> 01:16:57,180
you would have
some conditioning.

1194
01:16:57,180 --> 01:16:58,600
So you would tell
your model, OK,

1195
01:16:58,600 --> 01:17:01,660
given this prompts you're going
to start with all these mask

1196
01:17:01,660 --> 01:17:02,580
tokens.

1197
01:17:02,580 --> 01:17:08,420
Just try to predict
what the answer is.

1198
01:17:08,420 --> 01:17:12,700
So in case you're having
trouble with the intuition--

1199
01:17:12,700 --> 01:17:14,420
so I also had trouble
in the beginning.

1200
01:17:14,420 --> 01:17:18,180
Why would it make
sense for texts

1201
01:17:18,180 --> 01:17:20,740
to be solved in a
diffusion manner.

1202
01:17:20,740 --> 01:17:22,160
Because typically,
when you write,

1203
01:17:22,160 --> 01:17:24,100
you write one word at a time.

1204
01:17:24,100 --> 01:17:27,700
So one helpful way
to think about this

1205
01:17:27,700 --> 01:17:33,500
is let's suppose you
want to write a speech.

1206
01:17:33,500 --> 01:17:38,670
So you would not directly write
your speech in a linear way.

1207
01:17:38,670 --> 01:17:41,970
You would first
have a rough plan.

1208
01:17:41,970 --> 01:17:44,610
You say, OK, I'm going to talk
about this in the first place,

1209
01:17:44,610 --> 01:17:45,530
second, third.

1210
01:17:45,530 --> 01:17:47,830
You have some kind of drafts.

1211
01:17:47,830 --> 01:17:53,270
And then you try to refine what
is in each of these sections.

1212
01:17:53,270 --> 01:17:57,990
So you can think of diffusion
as kind of working like this.

1213
01:17:57,990 --> 01:18:06,150
So it tries to have a coarse to
find refinement of the outputs

1214
01:18:06,150 --> 01:18:09,230
so it can predict things that
are after a certain token that

1215
01:18:09,230 --> 01:18:10,250
has not been predicted.

1216
01:18:10,250 --> 01:18:14,910
But you can think of
this as being something

1217
01:18:14,910 --> 01:18:18,830
that goes from a very drafty
version to a very refined

1218
01:18:18,830 --> 01:18:21,550
version.

1219
01:18:21,550 --> 01:18:24,450
So that's what I think
about this process.

1220
01:18:24,450 --> 01:18:26,350
Hopefully, that's helpful.

1221
01:18:26,350 --> 01:18:31,830
And the key advantage here is
that the decoding is now done

1222
01:18:31,830 --> 01:18:36,790
in much fewer forward passes,
because previously you

1223
01:18:36,790 --> 01:18:44,430
had to do as many forward passes
as there are tokens to predict.

1224
01:18:44,430 --> 01:18:49,750
But here for diffusion, you
only need to do as many passes

1225
01:18:49,750 --> 01:18:54,030
as there are steps in
your diffusion process,

1226
01:18:54,030 --> 01:18:57,830
and the number of steps
is something you can fix.

1227
01:18:57,830 --> 01:19:00,510
So the higher the step,
the more high quality

1228
01:19:00,510 --> 01:19:04,790
your output is, but it's
typically much lower

1229
01:19:04,790 --> 01:19:09,630
than the length of your output.

1230
01:19:09,630 --> 01:19:16,070
So that is the core reason why
this model is so much faster

1231
01:19:16,070 --> 01:19:19,230
than the autoregressive one.

1232
01:19:19,230 --> 01:19:23,292
And of course, we don't
have that much time.

1233
01:19:23,292 --> 01:19:24,750
But in case you're
curious, in case

1234
01:19:24,750 --> 01:19:28,190
you're interested, after the
final, once you're completely

1235
01:19:28,190 --> 01:19:32,190
freed in terms of
things to think of,

1236
01:19:32,190 --> 01:19:36,632
just put some references
that could be helpful.

1237
01:19:36,632 --> 01:19:38,590
There's a paper that came
out earlier this year

1238
01:19:38,590 --> 01:19:47,090
called LLaDA, large language
diffusion model with masking.

1239
01:19:47,090 --> 01:19:49,010
Actually, I don't
remember the full acronym.

1240
01:19:49,010 --> 01:19:52,670
But it is actually
going through the math

1241
01:19:52,670 --> 01:19:56,510
and why the thing that
I just mentioned works.

1242
01:19:56,510 --> 01:19:58,190
And then there's a
bunch of other papers

1243
01:19:58,190 --> 01:19:59,970
that would also be helpful.

1244
01:19:59,970 --> 01:20:02,790
So the links are at
the bottom of the slide

1245
01:20:02,790 --> 01:20:06,110
in case you're interested.

1246
01:20:06,110 --> 01:20:09,470
And I just want to go
through two last things

1247
01:20:09,470 --> 01:20:12,470
before giving it to Shervine.

1248
01:20:12,470 --> 01:20:17,150
So first on the advantages
of this new paradigm.

1249
01:20:17,150 --> 01:20:21,190
So the first one is the speed.

1250
01:20:21,190 --> 01:20:24,270
So as we mentioned, it's
going to be much faster

1251
01:20:24,270 --> 01:20:28,080
than traditional
autoregressive models,

1252
01:20:28,080 --> 01:20:31,200
especially for outputs
that are longer.

1253
01:20:31,200 --> 01:20:34,600
And so some benchmarks, they
even say that it's something

1254
01:20:34,600 --> 01:20:38,600
along the lines of 10x faster.

1255
01:20:38,600 --> 01:20:44,000
So for cases like coding,
it can be very powerful

1256
01:20:44,000 --> 01:20:48,160
because you may have to
do several model calls.

1257
01:20:48,160 --> 01:20:53,260
And you as a user, you're just
waiting for that code to happen.

1258
01:20:53,260 --> 01:20:58,280
And just having a lower latency
makes a lot of difference.

1259
01:20:58,280 --> 01:21:03,240
The other thing is that
the nature of this approach

1260
01:21:03,240 --> 01:21:07,520
is actually considering
the text as a whole

1261
01:21:07,520 --> 01:21:09,920
in order to make
the predictions.

1262
01:21:09,920 --> 01:21:13,760
And so there is a
category of coding tasks

1263
01:21:13,760 --> 01:21:20,280
that are called fill in the
middle, which is about trying

1264
01:21:20,280 --> 01:21:24,120
to figure out-- you
have a bunch of codes,

1265
01:21:24,120 --> 01:21:28,840
and you want to know what's
missing in the middle.

1266
01:21:28,840 --> 01:21:30,460
And so fill in the middle.

1267
01:21:30,460 --> 01:21:34,200
And diffusion models are
typically better formulated

1268
01:21:34,200 --> 01:21:38,300
for these kinds of tasks because
they can consider, I guess,

1269
01:21:38,300 --> 01:21:41,920
input from multiple directions.

1270
01:21:41,920 --> 01:21:46,560
And that's why this
approach can be probably

1271
01:21:46,560 --> 01:21:53,080
something that can be useful
for some applications.

1272
01:21:53,080 --> 01:21:56,080
So in terms of the current
work, so these models,

1273
01:21:56,080 --> 01:21:56,980
they look great.

1274
01:21:56,980 --> 01:21:58,740
What I mentioned
to you looks great.

1275
01:21:58,740 --> 01:22:03,960
But the performance was not on
par with the current frontier

1276
01:22:03,960 --> 01:22:06,680
models, at least for some time.

1277
01:22:06,680 --> 01:22:09,840
But it's something
that may change.

1278
01:22:09,840 --> 01:22:12,040
So the papers that
I mentioned, they

1279
01:22:12,040 --> 01:22:14,280
are actually posting
performance that

1280
01:22:14,280 --> 01:22:19,280
is kind of catching up with the
models that are autoregressive.

1281
01:22:19,280 --> 01:22:21,800
So there is some
promise in there.

1282
01:22:21,800 --> 01:22:24,560
And then the other
line of work is just

1283
01:22:24,560 --> 01:22:29,850
to adapt all the techniques
that people have come up with.

1284
01:22:29,850 --> 01:22:32,070
Like for instance,
reasoning chains,

1285
01:22:32,070 --> 01:22:36,790
how do you adapt that
for diffusion, and so on.

1286
01:22:36,790 --> 01:22:39,330
There are so many techniques
that are intrinsically

1287
01:22:39,330 --> 01:22:44,570
more better suited for
autoregressive kinds of models

1288
01:22:44,570 --> 01:22:49,650
that can be adapted for that.

1289
01:22:49,650 --> 01:22:52,850
And that's what
people are working on.

1290
01:22:52,850 --> 01:22:57,970
So long story short,
what we saw was

1291
01:22:57,970 --> 01:23:03,550
that things we saw in this class
could be used in other domains.

1292
01:23:03,550 --> 01:23:08,570
For instance, we saw
the vision transformer

1293
01:23:08,570 --> 01:23:12,590
that was boring the transformer
for vision related tasks.

1294
01:23:12,590 --> 01:23:16,690
But we also saw that
things from other domains

1295
01:23:16,690 --> 01:23:20,250
could also be used
in the text world.

1296
01:23:20,250 --> 01:23:23,970
And that's what we saw
with diffusion LLMs.

1297
01:23:23,970 --> 01:23:27,090
And so this is probably, of
course, a subset of everything

1298
01:23:27,090 --> 01:23:30,090
that's happening.

1299
01:23:30,090 --> 01:23:32,410
And so with that, I
think we're concluding

1300
01:23:32,410 --> 01:23:35,090
our second item of our menu.

1301
01:23:35,090 --> 01:23:39,150
And I'm going to just
give it to Shervine.

1302
01:23:42,650 --> 01:23:44,570
Thank you, Afshine.

1303
01:23:44,570 --> 01:23:48,090
And with that, welcome to
the last part of the season

1304
01:23:48,090 --> 01:23:50,730
finale of CME 295.

1305
01:23:50,730 --> 01:23:54,010
And as Afshine mentioned, now
is the time for some closing

1306
01:23:54,010 --> 01:23:58,170
thoughts and see
what we can get away

1307
01:23:58,170 --> 01:24:05,690
from this class and the concepts
that are neighboring to it.

1308
01:24:05,690 --> 01:24:08,770
So first, Afshine went
through the concept

1309
01:24:08,770 --> 01:24:10,830
of diffusion and images.

1310
01:24:10,830 --> 01:24:12,550
And we saw some similarities.

1311
01:24:12,550 --> 01:24:14,570
We could draw with text.

1312
01:24:14,570 --> 01:24:18,010
And now we're going to see
what kinds of inspirations

1313
01:24:18,010 --> 01:24:21,530
have both modalities
taken from each other.

1314
01:24:21,530 --> 01:24:25,890
And we're going to see that
actually, a lot of things

1315
01:24:25,890 --> 01:24:29,730
can be reused.

1316
01:24:29,730 --> 01:24:32,170
So the first thing
that I want to mention

1317
01:24:32,170 --> 01:24:36,610
in terms of what has been
reused is the architecture part.

1318
01:24:36,610 --> 01:24:41,170
So Afshine mentioned
these diffusion concept

1319
01:24:41,170 --> 01:24:44,310
that was born in
the field of images,

1320
01:24:44,310 --> 01:24:47,130
but that was taken
for text, and was

1321
01:24:47,130 --> 01:24:51,650
able to yield a lower latency
like higher speed ups, which

1322
01:24:51,650 --> 01:24:54,050
is great when you're an user.

1323
01:24:54,050 --> 01:24:57,570
So this was one
example of a win.

1324
01:24:57,570 --> 01:25:02,890
And then on the other
direction, traditionally, images

1325
01:25:02,890 --> 01:25:06,650
have been dealing with
convolutions mostly

1326
01:25:06,650 --> 01:25:10,890
as model architecture type.

1327
01:25:10,890 --> 01:25:15,330
But these papers saw that
replacing convolutions

1328
01:25:15,330 --> 01:25:21,680
with transformers was very good,
even yielding better results.

1329
01:25:21,680 --> 01:25:24,700
So all these latest
diffusion-based papers

1330
01:25:24,700 --> 01:25:29,220
in the field of images
typically use transformers.

1331
01:25:29,220 --> 01:25:31,460
And here, I'm linking
one of the papers

1332
01:25:31,460 --> 01:25:36,980
that Afshine already
briefly went through.

1333
01:25:36,980 --> 01:25:41,980
But not only is it the
architecture side that

1334
01:25:41,980 --> 01:25:46,400
is the subject of pollination
between these modalities,

1335
01:25:46,400 --> 01:25:49,180
you could even
think of other kinds

1336
01:25:49,180 --> 01:25:51,620
of components like the input.

1337
01:25:51,620 --> 01:25:54,700
And for this one,
I want to mention

1338
01:25:54,700 --> 01:25:57,860
the example of DeepSeek OCR.

1339
01:25:57,860 --> 01:25:59,920
So I don't know if you've
heard of this paper.

1340
01:25:59,920 --> 01:26:02,260
It just came out very recently.

1341
01:26:02,260 --> 01:26:06,520
And contrary to what
the name suggests,

1342
01:26:06,520 --> 01:26:13,300
so OCR stands for optical
character recognition.

1343
01:26:13,300 --> 01:26:17,780
And it's usually a field
that tries to converts

1344
01:26:17,780 --> 01:26:21,180
some scanned image into text.

1345
01:26:21,180 --> 01:26:26,020
But actually, that paper
doesn't boast some improvements

1346
01:26:26,020 --> 01:26:28,860
on the OCR task itself.

1347
01:26:28,860 --> 01:26:31,340
Rather, it showed
that you could learn

1348
01:26:31,340 --> 01:26:38,340
some function that
reconstructs text tokens based

1349
01:26:38,340 --> 01:26:40,460
on vision tokens.

1350
01:26:40,460 --> 01:26:42,340
And not only on vision tokens.

1351
01:26:42,340 --> 01:26:44,720
On very few vision tokens.

1352
01:26:44,720 --> 01:26:48,060
So it showed that
the representation

1353
01:26:48,060 --> 01:26:53,820
power of patches of images
as tokens was very strong.

1354
01:26:53,820 --> 01:26:58,600
And you have some researchers
that bring some rationale to it

1355
01:26:58,600 --> 01:27:03,220
like Hey Tokenizers are
not the best tool anyway.

1356
01:27:03,220 --> 01:27:06,780
And the things in patches
convey the meaning of texts

1357
01:27:06,780 --> 01:27:09,660
already with the
example of emojis

1358
01:27:09,660 --> 01:27:11,780
and so on that you
would otherwise

1359
01:27:11,780 --> 01:27:17,140
need to represent with
way more tokens in text.

1360
01:27:17,140 --> 01:27:19,340
And then another example
I want to mention

1361
01:27:19,340 --> 01:27:23,100
is even when you look
inside the architectures,

1362
01:27:23,100 --> 01:27:28,620
some of the tricks can be reused
and adapted in each field.

1363
01:27:28,620 --> 01:27:30,460
So here, I'm
mentioning the example

1364
01:27:30,460 --> 01:27:34,740
of rope, which Afshine
mentioned in the recap that

1365
01:27:34,740 --> 01:27:40,020
was used in texts to represent
the relative position of tokens.

1366
01:27:40,020 --> 01:27:44,840
And in the case of images
or even multi-modal setting,

1367
01:27:44,840 --> 01:27:50,180
where you have the presence
of both text and image within

1368
01:27:50,180 --> 01:27:55,540
the architecture, you're
able to adapt that trick

1369
01:27:55,540 --> 01:27:59,100
by reformulating it in 2D.

1370
01:27:59,100 --> 01:28:04,900
So here the figure shows how
you can attribute rope positions

1371
01:28:04,900 --> 01:28:09,500
in the two degrees, and how you
could place text tokens such

1372
01:28:09,500 --> 01:28:13,880
that the relative computation
of position still makes sense.

1373
01:28:17,230 --> 01:28:21,670
And even beyond
that, I would say

1374
01:28:21,670 --> 01:28:26,990
that the ongoing research for
transformers is very much alive

1375
01:28:26,990 --> 01:28:29,950
and people are still
figuring out all the details

1376
01:28:29,950 --> 01:28:32,030
that we're working with today.

1377
01:28:32,030 --> 01:28:34,630
And you see refinements
all the time

1378
01:28:34,630 --> 01:28:37,170
coming in terms of new papers.

1379
01:28:37,170 --> 01:28:42,310
So it's something that
is still developing.

1380
01:28:42,310 --> 01:28:46,990
And you can look at it
from multiple angles.

1381
01:28:46,990 --> 01:28:50,790
One is each of these design
decisions that we've had,

1382
01:28:50,790 --> 01:28:53,290
they are still
being iterated on.

1383
01:28:53,290 --> 01:28:57,310
So I'm listing a few
items here as an example.

1384
01:28:57,310 --> 01:29:00,750
So one is the optimizer side.

1385
01:29:00,750 --> 01:29:04,190
You might be familiar with the
Adam optimizer and its update

1386
01:29:04,190 --> 01:29:08,350
rule, which has been
popular for quite some time.

1387
01:29:08,350 --> 01:29:13,770
And it seems that state is being
challenged with newer papers.

1388
01:29:13,770 --> 01:29:18,550
So I referenced here
the Kimi K2 paper

1389
01:29:18,550 --> 01:29:22,470
that came out a few
months ago that introduces

1390
01:29:22,470 --> 01:29:25,110
a new kind of
optimizer called Muon.

1391
01:29:25,110 --> 01:29:28,550
And the latest version
of that MuonClip

1392
01:29:28,550 --> 01:29:33,070
seems to be a potential
candidate for this optimizer

1393
01:29:33,070 --> 01:29:35,270
to become the new standard.

1394
01:29:35,270 --> 01:29:43,270
So this field, even as basic as
it can be, is still developing.

1395
01:29:43,270 --> 01:29:45,650
But it's not only
the optimizer side.

1396
01:29:45,650 --> 01:29:48,550
You also have the
topic of normalization,

1397
01:29:48,550 --> 01:29:51,750
where Afshine mentioned
that the difference

1398
01:29:51,750 --> 01:29:54,150
between the original
transformer paper

1399
01:29:54,150 --> 01:29:58,630
and what you see
today in LLM papers,

1400
01:29:58,630 --> 01:30:01,330
you don't have the same kind
of normalization anymore.

1401
01:30:01,330 --> 01:30:04,590
In the past, you had post norm.

1402
01:30:04,590 --> 01:30:08,910
But now you have pre norm, which
brings the normalization earlier

1403
01:30:08,910 --> 01:30:12,760
on in the layer.

1404
01:30:12,760 --> 01:30:17,820
But beyond that design choice of
the location of normalization,

1405
01:30:17,820 --> 01:30:23,900
you even have the type of
normalization that changes.

1406
01:30:23,900 --> 01:30:28,160
So the transformer
paper used layer norm.

1407
01:30:28,160 --> 01:30:31,560
But these days, you might see
other kinds of normalization

1408
01:30:31,560 --> 01:30:36,340
techniques like RMS norm which
uses less parameters and others.

1409
01:30:36,340 --> 01:30:42,280
So the theory behind
it is not set just yet.

1410
01:30:42,280 --> 01:30:45,560
So you have other
kinds of parameters.

1411
01:30:45,560 --> 01:30:50,200
I've seen mentioned the
grouped query attention paper.

1412
01:30:50,200 --> 01:30:55,700
And you see these days in LLM
papers, not a fixed design.

1413
01:30:55,700 --> 01:30:59,460
Rather every paper adopts
their own technique.

1414
01:30:59,460 --> 01:31:05,100
Sometimes you see one kind of
attention used as a given layer,

1415
01:31:05,100 --> 01:31:08,560
but then it switches,
and different papers take

1416
01:31:08,560 --> 01:31:10,420
different design decisions.

1417
01:31:10,420 --> 01:31:13,280
So it's not set in stone.

1418
01:31:13,280 --> 01:31:16,020
Then you also have
activation functions.

1419
01:31:16,020 --> 01:31:19,480
So traditionally, in deep
learning, a lot of emphasis

1420
01:31:19,480 --> 01:31:23,720
was put on ReLU,
which is a very simple

1421
01:31:23,720 --> 01:31:26,240
and used worked very well.

1422
01:31:26,240 --> 01:31:29,040
But in the world
of LLMs, the shift

1423
01:31:29,040 --> 01:31:36,360
was towards ReLU like activation
functions, but not exactly ReLU.

1424
01:31:36,360 --> 01:31:40,400
So you had a Gaussian
error, linear units

1425
01:31:40,400 --> 01:31:42,120
you had other kinds.

1426
01:31:42,120 --> 01:31:44,460
And the research there
is still ongoing.

1427
01:31:44,460 --> 01:31:51,000
So you still see new activation
functions coming in now

1428
01:31:51,000 --> 01:31:52,480
and then.

1429
01:31:52,480 --> 01:31:54,480
And then you have
also whether to take

1430
01:31:54,480 --> 01:32:00,600
the design option of considering
the LLM as an MOE or not.

1431
01:32:00,600 --> 01:32:03,760
And even the number
of layers of your LLM

1432
01:32:03,760 --> 01:32:08,560
and other hyperparameters
like number of heads.

1433
01:32:08,560 --> 01:32:13,200
Size of the number of units
in the FFN, all of that

1434
01:32:13,200 --> 01:32:16,900
is still up for debate in
terms of design decisions.

1435
01:32:16,900 --> 01:32:19,920
So it's not fixed.

1436
01:32:19,920 --> 01:32:23,040
And then another area of
research I want to mention

1437
01:32:23,040 --> 01:32:27,160
is the data part,
which is crucial.

1438
01:32:27,160 --> 01:32:33,280
So the first LLMs, they enjoyed
a relatively clean state

1439
01:32:33,280 --> 01:32:36,280
of things because you
could scrape the internet

1440
01:32:36,280 --> 01:32:41,720
and hope for a lot of data that
was for sure human generated.

1441
01:32:41,720 --> 01:32:47,220
So you could learn these
patterns from, quote unquote,

1442
01:32:47,220 --> 01:32:51,400
a high quality source, even
though it's not in high quality

1443
01:32:51,400 --> 01:32:53,620
format when you look at
typical internet data,

1444
01:32:53,620 --> 01:32:57,760
but it was still
generated by human.

1445
01:32:57,760 --> 01:33:00,100
So these days, the
state has changed.

1446
01:33:00,100 --> 01:33:04,220
You type anything you want in
your favorite search browser.

1447
01:33:04,220 --> 01:33:08,470
Chances are the first results
are 80% LLM generated.

1448
01:33:08,470 --> 01:33:10,690
So are we doomed?

1449
01:33:10,690 --> 01:33:16,690
Maybe not, because actually
you see the development more

1450
01:33:16,690 --> 01:33:19,410
and more work in data curation.

1451
01:33:19,410 --> 01:33:22,130
So in the past, you would
just scrape the whole internet

1452
01:33:22,130 --> 01:33:24,730
and train next token
prediction on it.

1453
01:33:24,730 --> 01:33:28,490
But now, you have more and more
of this work of curating data

1454
01:33:28,490 --> 01:33:29,950
sets of interest.

1455
01:33:29,950 --> 01:33:32,170
And you have companies
that work on it.

1456
01:33:32,170 --> 01:33:38,070
And you have the emergence
of newer fine tuning modes.

1457
01:33:38,070 --> 01:33:40,570
So in the past, you had
pre-training and then fine

1458
01:33:40,570 --> 01:33:41,690
tuning.

1459
01:33:41,690 --> 01:33:45,690
Now you have pre-training,
mid training, and fine tuning.

1460
01:33:45,690 --> 01:33:50,530
And the mid training part trains
still on a large corpus of data,

1461
01:33:50,530 --> 01:33:52,450
but higher quality.

1462
01:33:52,450 --> 01:33:55,770
So people are finding
ways around it.

1463
01:33:55,770 --> 01:33:59,250
And I would say the
picture is not all grim,

1464
01:33:59,250 --> 01:34:04,050
but it's just that we need to
do more work in order to have

1465
01:34:04,050 --> 01:34:05,850
meaningful data at hand.

1466
01:34:05,850 --> 01:34:09,810
And the paper that is linked
at the bottom of the slide

1467
01:34:09,810 --> 01:34:14,210
is dealing with the
phenomenon of what

1468
01:34:14,210 --> 01:34:17,170
if you were training
on LLM generated data

1469
01:34:17,170 --> 01:34:21,330
and it's talking about a
concept called model collapse.

1470
01:34:21,330 --> 01:34:28,730
And it says that LLM generated
text is typically less diverse.

1471
01:34:28,730 --> 01:34:32,650
So the data distribution that
you would see at training time

1472
01:34:32,650 --> 01:34:36,530
changes and it leads to
less meaningful learning

1473
01:34:36,530 --> 01:34:39,730
at training time, which
is why it's typically bad.

1474
01:34:39,730 --> 01:34:45,650
And it motivates the need for
more work on the data part.

1475
01:34:45,650 --> 01:34:47,690
OK, nice.

1476
01:34:47,690 --> 01:34:51,790
And then even taking a step
back on the very architecture

1477
01:34:51,790 --> 01:34:55,030
we've been using all along.

1478
01:34:55,030 --> 01:34:58,810
Is it the best one?
it's not clear.

1479
01:34:58,810 --> 01:35:02,210
So that itself is
an area of research.

1480
01:35:02,210 --> 01:35:05,930
And future
breakthroughs might come

1481
01:35:05,930 --> 01:35:09,150
from redesigning
this architecture.

1482
01:35:11,810 --> 01:35:16,370
So in the past few years,
a lot of the research

1483
01:35:16,370 --> 01:35:21,450
that we have seen has been
on improving benchmarks

1484
01:35:21,450 --> 01:35:23,590
even more each time.

1485
01:35:23,590 --> 01:35:24,990
So you have a set of benchmarks.

1486
01:35:24,990 --> 01:35:27,750
Everyone tries to
get the best results.

1487
01:35:27,750 --> 01:35:30,050
So it's a natural
trend because you

1488
01:35:30,050 --> 01:35:31,650
want to have more
and more powerful

1489
01:35:31,650 --> 01:35:36,170
models that fulfill
all your use cases.

1490
01:35:36,170 --> 01:35:39,330
But let's say we reach a
point where all the use

1491
01:35:39,330 --> 01:35:42,810
cases we care about are solved.

1492
01:35:42,810 --> 01:35:44,770
Then what?

1493
01:35:44,770 --> 01:35:47,890
So I think we're going
to see the emergence

1494
01:35:47,890 --> 01:35:51,810
of these second border
of the Pareto frontier,

1495
01:35:51,810 --> 01:35:58,210
where we care most about
making predictions from LLM

1496
01:35:58,210 --> 01:36:03,380
cost effective and
still very high quality.

1497
01:36:03,380 --> 01:36:10,540
So we see this emergence of
smaller and smaller LLMs.

1498
01:36:10,540 --> 01:36:13,060
I think it has been
dubbed small language

1499
01:36:13,060 --> 01:36:16,860
models, SLM, in the literature.

1500
01:36:16,860 --> 01:36:21,860
And typically, you hear
sometimes LLM providers

1501
01:36:21,860 --> 01:36:26,220
