which is the hardware part.

1509
01:36:51,700 --> 01:36:56,780
So typically, the kind of device
that you use to train these LLMs

1510
01:36:56,780 --> 01:37:00,220
are GPUs, which are
great at one thing--

1511
01:37:00,220 --> 01:37:02,420
matrix multiply.

1512
01:37:02,420 --> 01:37:06,140
But the thing is, we've kept
these kinds of architectures

1513
01:37:06,140 --> 01:37:10,140
to train our models, even though
the architecture doesn't only

1514
01:37:10,140 --> 01:37:18,580
need matrix multiplies as
a foundational atomic unit

1515
01:37:18,580 --> 01:37:24,020
of compute, the self-attention
world and the transformer world

1516
01:37:24,020 --> 01:37:28,260
has all these special needs.

1517
01:37:28,260 --> 01:37:35,140
The qk transpose part we saw
was actually very expensive,

1518
01:37:35,140 --> 01:37:38,900
which has motivated papers
such as flash attention

1519
01:37:38,900 --> 01:37:43,180
to, as I've seen mentioned,
actually forego of some

1520
01:37:43,180 --> 01:37:47,180
of the data for the sake of
not doing too much movements

1521
01:37:47,180 --> 01:37:52,060
on the memory side, even
if it meant recomputing

1522
01:37:52,060 --> 01:37:53,920
the same things afterwards.

1523
01:37:53,920 --> 01:37:56,630
And then a lot of work
has been on optimizing

1524
01:37:56,630 --> 01:38:00,790
where the flow of memory
within the GPU resides.

1525
01:38:00,790 --> 01:38:07,830
And this shows that maybe you
need a more optimized hardware

1526
01:38:07,830 --> 01:38:15,070
architecture in order to
solve these use cases.

1527
01:38:15,070 --> 01:38:18,550
So there is a recent
paper that came out

1528
01:38:18,550 --> 01:38:22,390
that actually encodes
all of these operations

1529
01:38:22,390 --> 01:38:24,310
as part of the hardware.

1530
01:38:24,310 --> 01:38:29,030
So in the past,
the core operation

1531
01:38:29,030 --> 01:38:32,370
that the GPU was great
at is matrix multiply.

1532
01:38:32,370 --> 01:38:36,390
And based on it, you try to
build all of the input output

1533
01:38:36,390 --> 01:38:38,070
that you want.

1534
01:38:38,070 --> 01:38:42,830
But here this paper that came
out, I think, in September

1535
01:38:42,830 --> 01:38:46,070
shows a proof of
concept where you

1536
01:38:46,070 --> 01:38:49,950
can do all of these
computations as a side

1537
01:38:49,950 --> 01:38:55,230
effect of implementing input
and outputs with analog signals.

1538
01:38:55,230 --> 01:38:58,270
So you have all of these
computations that are embedded

1539
01:38:58,270 --> 01:38:59,870
as part of the hardware.

1540
01:38:59,870 --> 01:39:05,150
And based on pulses as input
that simulates your array

1541
01:39:05,150 --> 01:39:10,270
values, these
hardware architectures

1542
01:39:10,270 --> 01:39:12,630
have some physical
properties, you

1543
01:39:12,630 --> 01:39:19,030
could think of a Kirchhoff
law in the field of, I think,

1544
01:39:19,030 --> 01:39:20,430
intensity.

1545
01:39:20,430 --> 01:39:22,710
You can add them up.

1546
01:39:22,710 --> 01:39:28,070
And it uses properties like this
to have what you need as inputs

1547
01:39:28,070 --> 01:39:34,750
and just read out the
results as output.

1548
01:39:34,750 --> 01:39:39,990
So when the paper simulated
this kind of architecture,

1549
01:39:39,990 --> 01:39:44,830
they observed, without too
much surprise quite a bit

1550
01:39:44,830 --> 01:39:46,910
of improvement
both on the latency

1551
01:39:46,910 --> 01:39:50,870
and energy saving
parts both explained

1552
01:39:50,870 --> 01:39:54,230
because you don't need to do
the computations yourself.

1553
01:39:54,230 --> 01:39:58,690
You just get them as a side
effect of your hardware.

